100 /*!
101 @brief unnamed namespace with internal helper functions
102 @since version 1.0.0

104 namespace
105 {
106 /*!
107 @brief Helper to determine whether there's a key_type for T.
108 
109 Thus helper is used to tell associative containers apart from other containers
110 such as sequence containers. For instance, `std::map` passes the test as it
111 contains a `mapped_type`, whereas `std::vector` fails the test.
112 
113 @sa http://stackoverflow.com/a/7728728/266378
114 @since version 1.0.0, overworked in version 2.0.6
115 */
116 template<typename T>
117 struct has_mapped_type
118 {
119  private:
120  template <typename U, typename = typename U::mapped_type>
121  static int detect(U&&);
122 
123  static void detect(...);
124  public:
125  static constexpr bool value =
126  std::is_integral<decltype(detect(std::declval<T>()))>::value;
127 };
128 
129 } // namespace
130 
131 /*!
132 @brief a class to store JSON values
133 
134 @tparam ObjectType type for JSON objects (`std::map` by default; will be used
135 in @ref object_t)
136 @tparam ArrayType type for JSON arrays (`std::vector` by default; will be used
137 in @ref array_t)
138 @tparam StringType type for JSON strings and object keys (`std::string` by
139 default; will be used in @ref string_t)
140 @tparam BooleanType type for JSON booleans (`bool` by default; will be used
141 in @ref boolean_t)
142 @tparam NumberIntegerType type for JSON integer numbers (`int64_t` by
143 default; will be used in @ref number_integer_t)
144 @tparam NumberUnsignedType type for JSON unsigned integer numbers (@c
145 `uint64_t` by default; will be used in @ref number_unsigned_t)
146 @tparam NumberFloatType type for JSON floating-point numbers (`double` by
147 default; will be used in @ref number_float_t)
148 @tparam AllocatorType type of the allocator to use (`std::allocator` by
149 default)
150 
151 @requirement The class satisfies the following concept requirements:
152 - Basic
153  - [DefaultConstructible](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/concept/DefaultConstructible):
154  JSON values can be default constructed. The result will be a JSON null
155  value.
156  - [MoveConstructible](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/concept/MoveConstructible):
157  A JSON value can be constructed from an rvalue argument.
158  - [CopyConstructible](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/concept/CopyConstructible):
159  A JSON value can be copy-constructed from an lvalue expression.
160  - [MoveAssignable](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/concept/MoveAssignable):
161  A JSON value van be assigned from an rvalue argument.
162  - [CopyAssignable](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/concept/CopyAssignable):
163  A JSON value can be copy-assigned from an lvalue expression.
164  - [Destructible](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/concept/Destructible):
165  JSON values can be destructed.
166 - Layout
167  - [StandardLayoutType](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/concept/StandardLayoutType):
168  JSON values have
169  [standard layout](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/language/data_members#Standard_layout):
170  All non-static data members are private and standard layout types, the
171  class has no virtual functions or (virtual) base classes.
172 - Library-wide
173  - [EqualityComparable](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/concept/EqualityComparable):
174  JSON values can be compared with `==`, see @ref
175  operator==(const_reference,const_reference).
176  - [LessThanComparable](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/concept/LessThanComparable):
177  JSON values can be compared with `<`, see @ref
178  operator<(const_reference,const_reference).
179  - [Swappable](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/concept/Swappable):
180  Any JSON lvalue or rvalue of can be swapped with any lvalue or rvalue of
181  other compatible types, using unqualified function call @ref swap().
182  - [NullablePointer](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/concept/NullablePointer):
183  JSON values can be compared against `std::nullptr_t` objects which are used
184  to model the `null` value.
185 - Container
186  - [Container](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/concept/Container):
187  JSON values can be used like STL containers and provide iterator access.
188  - [ReversibleContainer](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/concept/ReversibleContainer);
189  JSON values can be used like STL containers and provide reverse iterator
190  access.
191 
192 @invariant The member variables @a m_value and @a m_type have the following
193 relationship:
194 - If `m_type == value_t::object`, then `m_value.object != nullptr`.
195 - If `m_type == value_t::array`, then `m_value.array != nullptr`.
196 - If `m_type == value_t::string`, then `m_value.string != nullptr`.
197 The invariants are checked by member function assert_invariant().
198 
199 @internal
200 @note ObjectType trick from http://stackoverflow.com/a/9860911
201 @endinternal
202 
203 @see [RFC 7159: The JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) Data Interchange
204 Format](http://rfc7159.net/rfc7159)
205 
206 @since version 1.0.0
207 
208 @nosubgrouping
209 */
210 template <
211  template<typename U, typename V, typename... Args> class ObjectType = std::map,
212  template<typename U, typename... Args> class ArrayType = std::vector,
213  class StringType = std::string,
214  class BooleanType = bool,
215  class NumberIntegerType = std::int64_t,
216  class NumberUnsignedType = std::uint64_t,
217  class NumberFloatType = double,
218  template<typename U> class AllocatorType = std::allocator
219  >
220 class basic_json
221 {
222  private:
223  /// workaround type for MSVC
224  using basic_json_t = basic_json<ObjectType, ArrayType, StringType,
225  BooleanType, NumberIntegerType, NumberUnsignedType, NumberFloatType,
226  AllocatorType>;
227 
228  public:
229  // forward declarations
230  template<typename U> class iter_impl;
231  template<typename Base> class json_reverse_iterator;
232  class json_pointer;
233 
234  /////////////////////
235  // container types //
236  /////////////////////
237 
238  /// @name container types
239  /// The canonic container types to use @ref basic_json like any other STL
240  /// container.
241  /// @{
242 
243  /// the type of elements in a basic_json container
244  using value_type = basic_json;
245 
246  /// the type of an element reference
247  using reference = value_type&;
248  /// the type of an element const reference
249  using const_reference = const value_type&;
250 
251  /// a type to represent differences between iterators
252  using difference_type = std::ptrdiff_t;
253  /// a type to represent container sizes
254  using size_type = std::size_t;
255 
256  /// the allocator type
257  using allocator_type = AllocatorType<basic_json>;
258 
259  /// the type of an element pointer
260  using pointer = typename std::allocator_traits<allocator_type>::pointer;
261  /// the type of an element const pointer
262  using const_pointer = typename std::allocator_traits<allocator_type>::const_pointer;
263 
264  /// an iterator for a basic_json container
265  using iterator = iter_impl<basic_json>;
266  /// a const iterator for a basic_json container
267  using const_iterator = iter_impl<const basic_json>;
268  /// a reverse iterator for a basic_json container
269  using reverse_iterator = json_reverse_iterator<typename basic_json::iterator>;
270  /// a const reverse iterator for a basic_json container
271  using const_reverse_iterator = json_reverse_iterator<typename basic_json::const_iterator>;
272 
273  /// @}
274 
275 
276  /*!
277  @brief returns the allocator associated with the container
278  */
279  static allocator_type get_allocator()
280  {
281  return allocator_type();
282  }

291  result["copyright"] = "(C) 2013-2017 Niels Lohmann";
292  result["name"] = "JSON for Modern C++";
293  result["url"] = "https://github.com/nlohmann/json";
294  result["version"] =
295  {
296  {"string", "2.0.10"},
297  {"major", 2},
298  {"minor", 0},
299  {"patch", 10},
300  };
301 
302 #ifdef _WIN32
303  result["platform"] = "win32";
304 #elif defined __linux__
305  result["platform"] = "linux";
306 #elif defined __APPLE__
307  result["platform"] = "apple";
308 #elif defined __unix__
309  result["platform"] = "unix";
310 #else
311  result["platform"] = "unknown";
312 #endif
313 
314 #if defined(__clang__)
315  result["compiler"] = {{"family", "clang"}, {"version", __clang_version__}};
316 #elif defined(__ICC) || defined(__INTEL_COMPILER)
317  result["compiler"] = {{"family", "icc"}, {"version", __INTEL_COMPILER}};
318 #elif defined(__GNUC__) || defined(__GNUG__)

320 #elif defined(__HP_cc) || defined(__HP_aCC)
321  result["compiler"] = "hp"
322 #elif defined(__IBMCPP__)
323  result["compiler"] = {{"family", "ilecpp"}, {"version", __IBMCPP__}};
324 #elif defined(_MSC_VER)
325  result["compiler"] = {{"family", "msvc"}, {"version", _MSC_VER}};

336 #else
337  result["compiler"]["c++"] = "unknown";
338 #endif
339  return result;

343  ///////////////////////////
344  // JSON value data types //

346 
347  /// @name JSON value data types
348  /// The data types to store a JSON value. These types are derived from
349  /// the template arguments passed to class @ref basic_json.
350  /// @{
351 
352  /*!
353  @brief a type for an object
354 
355  [RFC 7159](http://rfc7159.net/rfc7159) describes JSON objects as follows:
356  > An object is an unordered collection of zero or more name/value pairs,
357  > where a name is a string and a value is a string, number, boolean, null,
358  > object, or array.
359 
360  To store objects in C++, a type is defined by the template parameters
361  described below.
362 
363  @tparam ObjectType the container to store objects (e.g., `std::map` or
364  `std::unordered_map`)
365  @tparam StringType the type of the keys or names (e.g., `std::string`).
366  The comparison function `std::less<StringType>` is used to order elements
367  inside the container.
368  @tparam AllocatorType the allocator to use for objects (e.g.,
369  `std::allocator`)
370 
371  #### Default type
372 
373  With the default values for @a ObjectType (`std::map`), @a StringType
374  (`std::string`), and @a AllocatorType (`std::allocator`), the default
375  value for @a object_t is:
376 
377  @code {.cpp}
378  std::map<
379  std::string, // key_type
380  basic_json, // value_type
381  std::less<std::string>, // key_compare
382  std::allocator<std::pair<const std::string, basic_json>> // allocator_type
383  >
384  @endcode
385 
386  #### Behavior
387 
388  The choice of @a object_t influences the behavior of the JSON class. With
389  the default type, objects have the following behavior:
390 
391  - When all names are unique, objects will be interoperable in the sense
392  that all software implementations receiving that object will agree on
393  the name-value mappings.
394  - When the names within an object are not unique, later stored name/value
395  pairs overwrite previously stored name/value pairs, leaving the used
396  names unique. For instance, `{"key": 1}` and `{"key": 2, "key": 1}` will
397  be treated as equal and both stored as `{"key": 1}`.
398  - Internally, name/value pairs are stored in lexicographical order of the
399  names. Objects will also be serialized (see @ref dump) in this order.
400  For instance, `{"b": 1, "a": 2}` and `{"a": 2, "b": 1}` will be stored
401  and serialized as `{"a": 2, "b": 1}`.
402  - When comparing objects, the order of the name/value pairs is irrelevant.
403  This makes objects interoperable in the sense that they will not be
404  affected by these differences. For instance, `{"b": 1, "a": 2}` and
405  `{"a": 2, "b": 1}` will be treated as equal.
406 
407  #### Limits
408 
409  [RFC 7159](http://rfc7159.net/rfc7159) specifies:
410  > An implementation may set limits on the maximum depth of nesting.
411 
412  In this class, the object's limit of nesting is not constraint explicitly.
413  However, a maximum depth of nesting may be introduced by the compiler or
414  runtime environment. A theoretical limit can be queried by calling the
415  @ref max_size function of a JSON object.
416 
417  #### Storage
418 
419  Objects are stored as pointers in a @ref basic_json type. That is, for any
420  access to object values, a pointer of type `object_t*` must be
421  dereferenced.
422 
423  @sa @ref array_t -- type for an array value
424 
425  @since version 1.0.0
426 
427  @note The order name/value pairs are added to the object is *not*
428  preserved by the library. Therefore, iterating an object may return
429  name/value pairs in a different order than they were originally stored. In
430  fact, keys will be traversed in alphabetical order as `std::map` with
431  `std::less` is used by default. Please note this behavior conforms to [RFC
432  7159](http://rfc7159.net/rfc7159), because any order implements the
433  specified "unordered" nature of JSON objects.
434  */
435  using object_t = ObjectType<StringType,
436  basic_json,
437  std::less<StringType>,
438  AllocatorType<std::pair<const StringType,
439  basic_json>>>;
440 
441  /*!
442  @brief a type for an array
443 
444  [RFC 7159](http://rfc7159.net/rfc7159) describes JSON arrays as follows:
445  > An array is an ordered sequence of zero or more values.
446 
447  To store objects in C++, a type is defined by the template parameters
448  explained below.
449 
450  @tparam ArrayType container type to store arrays (e.g., `std::vector` or
451  `std::list`)
452  @tparam AllocatorType allocator to use for arrays (e.g., `std::allocator`)
453 
454  #### Default type
455 
456  With the default values for @a ArrayType (`std::vector`) and @a
457  AllocatorType (`std::allocator`), the default value for @a array_t is:
458 
459  @code {.cpp}
460  std::vector<
461  basic_json, // value_type
462  std::allocator<basic_json> // allocator_type
463  >
464  @endcode
465 
466  #### Limits
467 
468  [RFC 7159](http://rfc7159.net/rfc7159) specifies:
469  > An implementation may set limits on the maximum depth of nesting.
470 
471  In this class, the array's limit of nesting is not constraint explicitly.
472  However, a maximum depth of nesting may be introduced by the compiler or
473  runtime environment. A theoretical limit can be queried by calling the
474  @ref max_size function of a JSON array.
475 
476  #### Storage
477 
478  Arrays are stored as pointers in a @ref basic_json type. That is, for any
479  access to array values, a pointer of type `array_t*` must be dereferenced.
480 
481  @sa @ref object_t -- type for an object value
482 
483  @since version 1.0.0
484  */
485  using array_t = ArrayType<basic_json, AllocatorType<basic_json>>;
486 
487  /*!
488  @brief a type for a string
489 
490  [RFC 7159](http://rfc7159.net/rfc7159) describes JSON strings as follows:
491  > A string is a sequence of zero or more Unicode characters.
492 
493  To store objects in C++, a type is defined by the template parameter
494  described below. Unicode values are split by the JSON class into
495  byte-sized characters during deserialization.
496 
497  @tparam StringType the container to store strings (e.g., `std::string`).
498  Note this container is used for keys/names in objects, see @ref object_t.
499 
500  #### Default type
501 
502  With the default values for @a StringType (`std::string`), the default
503  value for @a string_t is:
504 
505  @code {.cpp}
506  std::string
507  @endcode
508 
509  #### Encoding
510 
511  Strings are stored in UTF-8 encoding. Therefore, functions like
512  `std::string::size()` or `std::string::length()` return the number of
513  bytes in the string rather than the number of characters or glyphs.
514 
515  #### String comparison
516 
517  [RFC 7159](http://rfc7159.net/rfc7159) states:
518  > Software implementations are typically required to test names of object
519  > members for equality. Implementations that transform the textual
520  > representation into sequences of Unicode code units and then perform the
521  > comparison numerically, code unit by code unit, are interoperable in the
522  > sense that implementations will agree in all cases on equality or
523  > inequality of two strings. For example, implementations that compare
524  > strings with escaped characters unconverted may incorrectly find that
525  > `"a\\b"` and `"a\u005Cb"` are not equal.
526 
527  This implementation is interoperable as it does compare strings code unit
528  by code unit.
529 
530  #### Storage
531 
532  String values are stored as pointers in a @ref basic_json type. That is,
533  for any access to string values, a pointer of type `string_t*` must be
534  dereferenced.
535 
536  @since version 1.0.0
537  */
538  using string_t = StringType;
539 
540  /*!
541  @brief a type for a boolean
542 
543  [RFC 7159](http://rfc7159.net/rfc7159) implicitly describes a boolean as a
544  type which differentiates the two literals `true` and `false`.
545 
546  To store objects in C++, a type is defined by the template parameter @a
547  BooleanType which chooses the type to use.
548 
549  #### Default type
550 
551  With the default values for @a BooleanType (`bool`), the default value for
552  @a boolean_t is:
553 
554  @code {.cpp}
555  bool
556  @endcode
557 
558  #### Storage
559 
560  Boolean values are stored directly inside a @ref basic_json type.
561 
562  @since version 1.0.0
563  */
564  using boolean_t = BooleanType;
565 
566  /*!
567  @brief a type for a number (integer)
568 
569  [RFC 7159](http://rfc7159.net/rfc7159) describes numbers as follows:
570  > The representation of numbers is similar to that used in most
571  > programming languages. A number is represented in base 10 using decimal
572  > digits. It contains an integer component that may be prefixed with an
573  > optional minus sign, which may be followed by a fraction part and/or an
574  > exponent part. Leading zeros are not allowed. (...) Numeric values that
575  > cannot be represented in the grammar below (such as Infinity and NaN)
576  > are not permitted.
577 
578  This description includes both integer and floating-point numbers.
579  However, C++ allows more precise storage if it is known whether the number
580  is a signed integer, an unsigned integer or a floating-point number.
581  Therefore, three different types, @ref number_integer_t, @ref
582  number_unsigned_t and @ref number_float_t are used.
583 
584  To store integer numbers in C++, a type is defined by the template
585  parameter @a NumberIntegerType which chooses the type to use.
586 
587  #### Default type
588 
589  With the default values for @a NumberIntegerType (`int64_t`), the default
590  value for @a number_integer_t is:
591 
592  @code {.cpp}
593  int64_t
594  @endcode
595 
596  #### Default behavior
597 
598  - The restrictions about leading zeros is not enforced in C++. Instead,
599  leading zeros in integer literals lead to an interpretation as octal
600  number. Internally, the value will be stored as decimal number. For
601  instance, the C++ integer literal `010` will be serialized to `8`.
602  During deserialization, leading zeros yield an error.
603  - Not-a-number (NaN) values will be serialized to `null`.
604 
605  #### Limits
606 
607  [RFC 7159](http://rfc7159.net/rfc7159) specifies:
608  > An implementation may set limits on the range and precision of numbers.
609 
610  When the default type is used, the maximal integer number that can be
611  stored is `9223372036854775807` (INT64_MAX) and the minimal integer number
612  that can be stored is `-9223372036854775808` (INT64_MIN). Integer numbers
613  that are out of range will yield over/underflow when used in a
614  constructor. During deserialization, too large or small integer numbers
615  will be automatically be stored as @ref number_unsigned_t or @ref
616  number_float_t.
617 
618  [RFC 7159](http://rfc7159.net/rfc7159) further states:
619  > Note that when such software is used, numbers that are integers and are
620  > in the range \f$[-2^{53}+1, 2^{53}-1]\f$ are interoperable in the sense
621  > that implementations will agree exactly on their numeric values.
622 
623  As this range is a subrange of the exactly supported range [INT64_MIN,
624  INT64_MAX], this class's integer type is interoperable.
625 
626  #### Storage
627 
628  Integer number values are stored directly inside a @ref basic_json type.
629 
630  @sa @ref number_float_t -- type for number values (floating-point)
631 
632  @sa @ref number_unsigned_t -- type for number values (unsigned integer)
633 
634  @since version 1.0.0
635  */
636  using number_integer_t = NumberIntegerType;
637 
638  /*!
639  @brief a type for a number (unsigned)
640 
641  [RFC 7159](http://rfc7159.net/rfc7159) describes numbers as follows:
642  > The representation of numbers is similar to that used in most
643  > programming languages. A number is represented in base 10 using decimal
644  > digits. It contains an integer component that may be prefixed with an
645  > optional minus sign, which may be followed by a fraction part and/or an
646  > exponent part. Leading zeros are not allowed. (...) Numeric values that
647  > cannot be represented in the grammar below (such as Infinity and NaN)
648  > are not permitted.
649 
650  This description includes both integer and floating-point numbers.
651  However, C++ allows more precise storage if it is known whether the number
652  is a signed integer, an unsigned integer or a floating-point number.
653  Therefore, three different types, @ref number_integer_t, @ref
654  number_unsigned_t and @ref number_float_t are used.
655 
656  To store unsigned integer numbers in C++, a type is defined by the
657  template parameter @a NumberUnsignedType which chooses the type to use.
658 
659  #### Default type
660 
661  With the default values for @a NumberUnsignedType (`uint64_t`), the
662  default value for @a number_unsigned_t is:
663 
664  @code {.cpp}
665  uint64_t
666  @endcode
667 
668  #### Default behavior
669 
670  - The restrictions about leading zeros is not enforced in C++. Instead,
671  leading zeros in integer literals lead to an interpretation as octal
672  number. Internally, the value will be stored as decimal number. For
673  instance, the C++ integer literal `010` will be serialized to `8`.
674  During deserialization, leading zeros yield an error.
675  - Not-a-number (NaN) values will be serialized to `null`.
676 
677  #### Limits
678 
679  [RFC 7159](http://rfc7159.net/rfc7159) specifies:
680  > An implementation may set limits on the range and precision of numbers.
681 
682  When the default type is used, the maximal integer number that can be
683  stored is `18446744073709551615` (UINT64_MAX) and the minimal integer
684  number that can be stored is `0`. Integer numbers that are out of range
685  will yield over/underflow when used in a constructor. During
686  deserialization, too large or small integer numbers will be automatically
687  be stored as @ref number_integer_t or @ref number_float_t.
688 
689  [RFC 7159](http://rfc7159.net/rfc7159) further states:
690  > Note that when such software is used, numbers that are integers and are
691  > in the range \f$[-2^{53}+1, 2^{53}-1]\f$ are interoperable in the sense
692  > that implementations will agree exactly on their numeric values.
693 
694  As this range is a subrange (when considered in conjunction with the
695  number_integer_t type) of the exactly supported range [0, UINT64_MAX],
696  this class's integer type is interoperable.
697 
698  #### Storage
699 
700  Integer number values are stored directly inside a @ref basic_json type.
701 
702  @sa @ref number_float_t -- type for number values (floating-point)
703  @sa @ref number_integer_t -- type for number values (integer)
704 
705  @since version 2.0.0
706  */
707  using number_unsigned_t = NumberUnsignedType;
708 
709  /*!
710  @brief a type for a number (floating-point)
711 
712  [RFC 7159](http://rfc7159.net/rfc7159) describes numbers as follows:
713  > The representation of numbers is similar to that used in most
714  > programming languages. A number is represented in base 10 using decimal
715  > digits. It contains an integer component that may be prefixed with an
716  > optional minus sign, which may be followed by a fraction part and/or an
717  > exponent part. Leading zeros are not allowed. (...) Numeric values that
718  > cannot be represented in the grammar below (such as Infinity and NaN)
719  > are not permitted.
720 
721  This description includes both integer and floating-point numbers.
722  However, C++ allows more precise storage if it is known whether the number
723  is a signed integer, an unsigned integer or a floating-point number.
724  Therefore, three different types, @ref number_integer_t, @ref
725  number_unsigned_t and @ref number_float_t are used.
726 
727  To store floating-point numbers in C++, a type is defined by the template
728  parameter @a NumberFloatType which chooses the type to use.
729 
730  #### Default type
731 
732  With the default values for @a NumberFloatType (`double`), the default
733  value for @a number_float_t is:
734 
735  @code {.cpp}
736  double
737  @endcode
738 
739  #### Default behavior
740 
741  - The restrictions about leading zeros is not enforced in C++. Instead,
742  leading zeros in floating-point literals will be ignored. Internally,
743  the value will be stored as decimal number. For instance, the C++
744  floating-point literal `01.2` will be serialized to `1.2`. During
745  deserialization, leading zeros yield an error.
746  - Not-a-number (NaN) values will be serialized to `null`.
747 
748  #### Limits
749 
750  [RFC 7159](http://rfc7159.net/rfc7159) states:
751  > This specification allows implementations to set limits on the range and
752  > precision of numbers accepted. Since software that implements IEEE
753  > 754-2008 binary64 (double precision) numbers is generally available and
754  > widely used, good interoperability can be achieved by implementations
755  > that expect no more precision or range than these provide, in the sense
756  > that implementations will approximate JSON numbers within the expected
757  > precision.
758 
759  This implementation does exactly follow this approach, as it uses double
760  precision floating-point numbers. Note values smaller than
761  `-1.79769313486232e+308` and values greater than `1.79769313486232e+308`
762  will be stored as NaN internally and be serialized to `null`.
763 
764  #### Storage
765 
766  Floating-point number values are stored directly inside a @ref basic_json
767  type.
768 
769  @sa @ref number_integer_t -- type for number values (integer)
770 
771  @sa @ref number_unsigned_t -- type for number values (unsigned integer)
772 
773  @since version 1.0.0
774  */
775  using number_float_t = NumberFloatType;
776 
777  /// @}
778 
779 
780  ///////////////////////////
781  // JSON type enumeration //
782  ///////////////////////////
783 
784  /*!
785  @brief the JSON type enumeration
786 
787  This enumeration collects the different JSON types. It is internally used
788  to distinguish the stored values, and the functions @ref is_null(), @ref
789  is_object(), @ref is_array(), @ref is_string(), @ref is_boolean(), @ref
790  is_number() (with @ref is_number_integer(), @ref is_number_unsigned(), and
791  @ref is_number_float()), @ref is_discarded(), @ref is_primitive(), and
792  @ref is_structured() rely on it.
793 
794  @note There are three enumeration entries (number_integer,
795  number_unsigned, and number_float), because the library distinguishes
796  these three types for numbers: @ref number_unsigned_t is used for unsigned
797  integers, @ref number_integer_t is used for signed integers, and @ref
798  number_float_t is used for floating-point numbers or to approximate
799  integers which do not fit in the limits of their respective type.
800 
801  @sa @ref basic_json(const value_t value_type) -- create a JSON value with
802  the default value for a given type
803 
804  @since version 1.0.0
805  */
806  enum class value_t : uint8_t
807  {
808  null, ///< null value
809  object, ///< object (unordered set of name/value pairs)
810  array, ///< array (ordered collection of values)
811  string, ///< string value
812  boolean, ///< boolean value
813  number_integer, ///< number value (signed integer)
814  number_unsigned, ///< number value (unsigned integer)
815  number_float, ///< number value (floating-point)
816  discarded ///< discarded by the the parser callback function
817  };
818 
819 
820  private:
821 
822  /// helper for exception-safe object creation
823  template<typename T, typename... Args>
824  static T* create(Args&& ... args)
825  {
826  AllocatorType<T> alloc;
827  auto deleter = [&](T * object)
828  {
829  alloc.deallocate(object, 1);
830  };
831  std::unique_ptr<T, decltype(deleter)> object(alloc.allocate(1), deleter);
832  alloc.construct(object.get(), std::forward<Args>(args)...);
833  assert(object != nullptr);
834  return object.release();
835  }
836 
837  ////////////////////////
838  // JSON value storage //
839  ////////////////////////
840 
841  /*!
842  @brief a JSON value
843 
844  The actual storage for a JSON value of the @ref basic_json class. This
845  union combines the different storage types for the JSON value types
846  defined in @ref value_t.
847 
848  JSON type | value_t type | used type
849  --------- | --------------- | ------------------------
850  object | object | pointer to @ref object_t
851  array | array | pointer to @ref array_t
852  string | string | pointer to @ref string_t
853  boolean | boolean | @ref boolean_t
854  number | number_integer | @ref number_integer_t
855  number | number_unsigned | @ref number_unsigned_t
856  number | number_float | @ref number_float_t
857  null | null | *no value is stored*
858 
859  @note Variable-length types (objects, arrays, and strings) are stored as
860  pointers. The size of the union should not exceed 64 bits if the default
861  value types are used.
862 
863  @since version 1.0.0
864  */
865  union json_value
866  {
867  /// object (stored with pointer to save storage)
868  object_t* object;
869  /// array (stored with pointer to save storage)
870  array_t* array;
871  /// string (stored with pointer to save storage)
872  string_t* string;
873  /// boolean
874  boolean_t boolean;
875  /// number (integer)
876  number_integer_t number_integer;
877  /// number (unsigned integer)
878  number_unsigned_t number_unsigned;
879  /// number (floating-point)
880  number_float_t number_float;
881 
882  /// default constructor (for null values)
883  json_value() = default;
884  /// constructor for booleans
885  json_value(boolean_t v) noexcept : boolean(v) {}
886  /// constructor for numbers (integer)
887  json_value(number_integer_t v) noexcept : number_integer(v) {}
888  /// constructor for numbers (unsigned)
889  json_value(number_unsigned_t v) noexcept : number_unsigned(v) {}
890  /// constructor for numbers (floating-point)
891  json_value(number_float_t v) noexcept : number_float(v) {}
892  /// constructor for empty values of a given type
893  json_value(value_t t)
894  {
895  switch (t)
896  {
897  case value_t::object:
898  {
899  object = create<object_t>();
900  break;
901  }
902 
903  case value_t::array:
904  {
905  array = create<array_t>();
906  break;
907  }
908 
909  case value_t::string:
910  {
911  string = create<string_t>("");
912  break;
913  }
914 
915  case value_t::boolean:
916  {
917  boolean = boolean_t(false);
918  break;
919  }
920 
921  case value_t::number_integer:
922  {
923  number_integer = number_integer_t(0);
924  break;
925  }
926 
927  case value_t::number_unsigned:
928  {
929  number_unsigned = number_unsigned_t(0);
930  break;
931  }
932 
933  case value_t::number_float:
934  {
935  number_float = number_float_t(0.0);
936  break;
937  }
938 
939  case value_t::null:
940  {
941  break;
942  }
943 
944  default:
945  {
946  if (t == value_t::null)
947  {
948  throw std::domain_error("961c151d2e87f2686a955a9be24d316f1362bf21 2.0.10"); // LCOV_EXCL_LINE
949  }
950  break;
951  }
952  }
953  }
954 
955  /// constructor for strings
956  json_value(const string_t& value)
957  {
958  string = create<string_t>(value);
959  }
960 
961  /// constructor for objects
962  json_value(const object_t& value)
963  {
964  object = create<object_t>(value);
965  }
966 
967  /// constructor for arrays
968  json_value(const array_t& value)
969  {
970  array = create<array_t>(value);
971  }
972  };
973 
974  /*!
975  @brief checks the class invariants
976 
977  This function asserts the class invariants. It needs to be called at the
978  end of every constructor to make sure that created objects respect the
979  invariant. Furthermore, it has to be called each time the type of a JSON
980  value is changed, because the invariant expresses a relationship between
981  @a m_type and @a m_value.
982  */
983  void assert_invariant() const
984  {
985  assert(m_type != value_t::object or m_value.object != nullptr);
986  assert(m_type != value_t::array or m_value.array != nullptr);
987  assert(m_type != value_t::string or m_value.string != nullptr);
988  }
989 
990  public:
991  //////////////////////////
992  // JSON parser callback //
993  //////////////////////////
994 
995  /*!
996  @brief JSON callback events
997 
998  This enumeration lists the parser events that can trigger calling a
999  callback function of type @ref parser_callback_t during parsing.
1000 
1001  @image html callback_events.png "Example when certain parse events are triggered"
1002 
1003  @since version 1.0.0
1004  */
1005  enum class parse_event_t : uint8_t
1006  {
1007  /// the parser read `{` and started to process a JSON object
1008  object_start,
1009  /// the parser read `}` and finished processing a JSON object
1010  object_end,
1011  /// the parser read `[` and started to process a JSON array
1012  array_start,
1013  /// the parser read `]` and finished processing a JSON array
1014  array_end,
1015  /// the parser read a key of a value in an object
1016  key,
1017  /// the parser finished reading a JSON value
1018  value
1019  };
1020 
1021  /*!
1022  @brief per-element parser callback type
1023 
1024  With a parser callback function, the result of parsing a JSON text can be
1025  influenced. When passed to @ref parse(std::istream&, const
1026  parser_callback_t) or @ref parse(const CharT, const parser_callback_t),
1027  it is called on certain events (passed as @ref parse_event_t via parameter
1028  @a event) with a set recursion depth @a depth and context JSON value
1029  @a parsed. The return value of the callback function is a boolean
1030  indicating whether the element that emitted the callback shall be kept or
1031  not.
1032 
1033  We distinguish six scenarios (determined by the event type) in which the
1034  callback function can be called. The following table describes the values
1035  of the parameters @a depth, @a event, and @a parsed.
1036 
1037  parameter @a event | description | parameter @a depth | parameter @a parsed
1038  ------------------ | ----------- | ------------------ | -------------------
1039  parse_event_t::object_start | the parser read `{` and started to process a JSON object | depth of the parent of the JSON object | a JSON value with type discarded
1040  parse_event_t::key | the parser read a key of a value in an object | depth of the currently parsed JSON object | a JSON string containing the key
1041  parse_event_t::object_end | the parser read `}` and finished processing a JSON object | depth of the parent of the JSON object | the parsed JSON object
1042  parse_event_t::array_start | the parser read `[` and started to process a JSON array | depth of the parent of the JSON array | a JSON value with type discarded
1043  parse_event_t::array_end | the parser read `]` and finished processing a JSON array | depth of the parent of the JSON array | the parsed JSON array
1044  parse_event_t::value | the parser finished reading a JSON value | depth of the value | the parsed JSON value
1045 
1046  @image html callback_events.png "Example when certain parse events are triggered"
1047 
1048  Discarding a value (i.e., returning `false`) has different effects
1049  depending on the context in which function was called:
1050 
1051  - Discarded values in structured types are skipped. That is, the parser
1052  will behave as if the discarded value was never read.
1053  - In case a value outside a structured type is skipped, it is replaced
1054  with `null`. This case happens if the top-level element is skipped.
1055 
1056  @param[in] depth the depth of the recursion during parsing
1057 
1058  @param[in] event an event of type parse_event_t indicating the context in
1059  the callback function has been called
1060 
1061  @param[in,out] parsed the current intermediate parse result; note that
1062  writing to this value has no effect for parse_event_t::key events
1063 
1064  @return Whether the JSON value which called the function during parsing
1065  should be kept (`true`) or not (`false`). In the latter case, it is either
1066  skipped completely or replaced by an empty discarded object.
1067 
1068  @sa @ref parse(std::istream&, parser_callback_t) or
1069  @ref parse(const CharT, const parser_callback_t) for examples
1070 
1071  @since version 1.0.0
1072  */
1073  using parser_callback_t = std::function<bool(int depth,
1074  parse_event_t event,
1075  basic_json& parsed)>;
1076 
1077 
1078  //////////////////
1079  // constructors //
1080  //////////////////
1081 
1082  /// @name constructors and destructors
1083  /// Constructors of class @ref basic_json, copy/move constructor, copy
1084  /// assignment, static functions creating objects, and the destructor.
1085  /// @{
1086 
1087  /*!
1088  @brief create an empty value with a given type
1089 
1090  Create an empty JSON value with a given type. The value will be default
1091  initialized with an empty value which depends on the type:
1092 
1093  Value type | initial value
1094  ----------- | -------------
1095  null | `null`
1096  boolean | `false`
1097  string | `""`
1098  number | `0`
1099  object | `{}`
1100  array | `[]`
1101 
1102  @param[in] value_type the type of the value to create
1103 
1104  @complexity Constant.
1105 
1106  @throw std::bad_alloc if allocation for object, array, or string value
1107  fails
1108 
1109  @liveexample{The following code shows the constructor for different @ref
1110  value_t values,basic_json__value_t}
1111 
1112  @sa @ref basic_json(std::nullptr_t) -- create a `null` value
1113  @sa @ref basic_json(boolean_t value) -- create a boolean value
1114  @sa @ref basic_json(const string_t&) -- create a string value
1115  @sa @ref basic_json(const object_t&) -- create a object value
1116  @sa @ref basic_json(const array_t&) -- create a array value
1117  @sa @ref basic_json(const number_float_t) -- create a number
1118  (floating-point) value
1119  @sa @ref basic_json(const number_integer_t) -- create a number (integer)
1120  value
1121  @sa @ref basic_json(const number_unsigned_t) -- create a number (unsigned)
1122  value
1123 
1124  @since version 1.0.0
1125  */
1126  basic_json(const value_t value_type)

1130  }

1133  @brief create a null object

1136  (explicitly creating `null`) or no parameter (implicitly creating `null`).
1137  The passed null pointer itself is not read -- it is only used to choose
1138  the right constructor.

1156  /*!
1157  @brief create an object (explicit)

1177  {

1180 
1181  /*!
1182  @brief create an object (implicit)
1183 
1184  Create an object JSON value with a given content. This constructor allows
1185  any type @a CompatibleObjectType that can be used to construct values of
1186  type @ref object_t.
1187 
1188  @tparam CompatibleObjectType An object type whose `key_type` and
1189  `value_type` is compatible to @ref object_t. Examples include `std::map`,
1190  `std::unordered_map`, `std::multimap`, and `std::unordered_multimap` with
1191  a `key_type` of `std::string`, and a `value_type` from which a @ref
1192  basic_json value can be constructed.
1193 
1194  @param[in] val a value for the object
1195 
1196  @complexity Linear in the size of the passed @a val.
1197 
1198  @throw std::bad_alloc if allocation for object value fails
1199 
1200  @liveexample{The following code shows the constructor with several
1201  compatible object type parameters.,basic_json__CompatibleObjectType}
1202 
1203  @sa @ref basic_json(const object_t&) -- create an object value
1204 
1205  @since version 1.0.0
1206  */
1207  template<class CompatibleObjectType, typename std::enable_if<
1208  std::is_constructible<typename object_t::key_type, typename CompatibleObjectType::key_type>::value and
1209  std::is_constructible<basic_json, typename CompatibleObjectType::mapped_type>::value, int>::type = 0>
1210  basic_json(const CompatibleObjectType& val)
1211  : m_type(value_t::object)
1212  {
1213  using std::begin;
1214  using std::end;
1215  m_value.object = create<object_t>(begin(val), end(val));
1216  assert_invariant();
1217  }
1218

1220  @brief create an array (explicit)
1221 
1222  Create an array JSON value with a given content.

1234  from a compatible STL containers
1235

1244  /*!
1245  @brief create an array (implicit)
1246 
1247  Create an array JSON value with a given content. This constructor allows
1248  any type @a CompatibleArrayType that can be used to construct values of
1249  type @ref array_t.
1250 
1251  @tparam CompatibleArrayType An object type whose `value_type` is
1252  compatible to @ref array_t. Examples include `std::vector`, `std::deque`,
1253  `std::list`, `std::forward_list`, `std::array`, `std::set`,
1254  `std::unordered_set`, `std::multiset`, and `unordered_multiset` with a
1255  `value_type` from which a @ref basic_json value can be constructed.
1256 
1257  @param[in] val a value for the array
1258 
1259  @complexity Linear in the size of the passed @a val.
1260 
1261  @throw std::bad_alloc if allocation for array value fails
1262 
1263  @liveexample{The following code shows the constructor with several

1265 
1266  @sa @ref basic_json(const array_t&) -- create an array value
1267 
1268  @since version 1.0.0
1269  */
1270  template<class CompatibleArrayType, typename std::enable_if<
1271  not std::is_same<CompatibleArrayType, typename basic_json_t::iterator>::value and
1272  not std::is_same<CompatibleArrayType, typename basic_json_t::const_iterator>::value and
1273  not std::is_same<CompatibleArrayType, typename basic_json_t::reverse_iterator>::value and
1274  not std::is_same<CompatibleArrayType, typename basic_json_t::const_reverse_iterator>::value and
1275  not std::is_same<CompatibleArrayType, typename array_t::iterator>::value and
1276  not std::is_same<CompatibleArrayType, typename array_t::const_iterator>::value and
1277  std::is_constructible<basic_json, typename CompatibleArrayType::value_type>::value, int>::type = 0>
1278  basic_json(const CompatibleArrayType& val)
1279  : m_type(value_t::array)
1280  {
1281  using std::begin;
1282  using std::end;
1283  m_value.array = create<array_t>(begin(val), end(val));
1284  assert_invariant();
1285  }

1627  /*!
1628  @brief create a container (array or object) from an initializer list
1629 
1630  Creates a JSON value of type array or object from the passed initializer
1631  list @a init. In case @a type_deduction is `true` (default), the type of
1632  the JSON value to be created is deducted from the initializer list @a init
1633  according to the following rules:
1634 
1635  1. If the list is empty, an empty JSON object value `{}` is created.
1636  2. If the list consists of pairs whose first element is a string, a JSON
1637  object value is created where the first elements of the pairs are
1638  treated as keys and the second elements are as values.
1639  3. In all other cases, an array is created.
1640 
1641  The rules aim to create the best fit between a C++ initializer list and
1642  JSON values. The rationale is as follows:
1643 
1644  1. The empty initializer list is written as `{}` which is exactly an empty
1645  JSON object.
1646  2. C++ has now way of describing mapped types other than to list a list of
1647  pairs. As JSON requires that keys must be of type string, rule 2 is the
1648  weakest constraint one can pose on initializer lists to interpret them
1649  as an object.
1650  3. In all other cases, the initializer list could not be interpreted as
1651  JSON object type, so interpreting it as JSON array type is safe.
1652 
1653  With the rules described above, the following JSON values cannot be
1654  expressed by an initializer list:
1655 
1656  - the empty array (`[]`): use @ref array(std::initializer_list<basic_json>)
1657  with an empty initializer list in this case
1658  - arrays whose elements satisfy rule 2: use @ref
1659  array(std::initializer_list<basic_json>) with the same initializer list
1660  in this case
1661 
1662  @note When used without parentheses around an empty initializer list, @ref
1663  basic_json() is called instead of this function, yielding the JSON null
1664  value.
1665 
1666  @param[in] init initializer list with JSON values
1667 
1668  @param[in] type_deduction internal parameter; when set to `true`, the type
1669  of the JSON value is deducted from the initializer list @a init; when set
1670  to `false`, the type provided via @a manual_type is forced. This mode is
1671  used by the functions @ref array(std::initializer_list<basic_json>) and
1672  @ref object(std::initializer_list<basic_json>).
1673 
1674  @param[in] manual_type internal parameter; when @a type_deduction is set
1675  to `false`, the created JSON value will use the provided type (only @ref
1676  value_t::array and @ref value_t::object are valid); when @a type_deduction
1677  is set to `true`, this parameter has no effect
1678 
1679  @throw std::domain_error if @a type_deduction is `false`, @a manual_type
1680  is `value_t::object`, but @a init contains an element which is not a pair
1681  whose first element is a string; example: `"cannot create object from
1682  initializer list"`
1683 
1684  @complexity Linear in the size of the initializer list @a init.
1685 
1686  @liveexample{The example below shows how JSON values are created from
1687  initializer lists.,basic_json__list_init_t}
1688 
1689  @sa @ref array(std::initializer_list<basic_json>) -- create a JSON array
1690  value from an initializer list
1691  @sa @ref object(std::initializer_list<basic_json>) -- create a JSON object
1692  value from an initializer list
1693 
1694  @since version 1.0.0
1695  */
1696  basic_json(std::initializer_list<basic_json> init,
1697  bool type_deduction = true,
1698  value_t manual_type = value_t::array)
1699  {
1700  // check if each element is an array with two elements whose first
1701  // element is a string
1702  bool is_an_object = std::all_of(init.begin(), init.end(),
1703  [](const basic_json & element)
1704  {
1705  return element.is_array() and element.size() == 2 and element[0].is_string();
1706  });
1707 
1708  // adjust type if type deduction is not wanted
1709  if (not type_deduction)
1710  {
1711  // if array is wanted, do not create an object though possible
1712  if (manual_type == value_t::array)
1713  {
1714  is_an_object = false;
1715  }
1716 
1717  // if object is wanted but impossible, throw an exception
1718  if (manual_type == value_t::object and not is_an_object)
1719  {
1720  throw std::domain_error("cannot create object from initializer list");
1721  }
1722  }
1723 
1724  if (is_an_object)
1725  {
1726  // the initializer list is a list of pairs -> create object
1727  m_type = value_t::object;
1728  m_value = value_t::object;
1729 
1730  std::for_each(init.begin(), init.end(), [this](const basic_json & element)
1731  {
1732  m_value.object->emplace(*(element[0].m_value.string), element[1]);
1733  });
1734  }
1735  else
1736  {
1737  // the initializer list describes an array -> create array
1738  m_type = value_t::array;
1739  m_value.array = create<array_t>(init);
1740  }
1741 
1742  assert_invariant();
1743  }
1744 
1745  /*!
1746  @brief explicitly create an array from an initializer list
1747 
1748  Creates a JSON array value from a given initializer list. That is, given a
1749  list of values `a, b, c`, creates the JSON value `[a, b, c]`. If the
1750  initializer list is empty, the empty array `[]` is created.
1751 
1752  @note This function is only needed to express two edge cases that cannot
1753  be realized with the initializer list constructor (@ref
1754  basic_json(std::initializer_list<basic_json>, bool, value_t)). These cases
1755  are:
1756  1. creating an array whose elements are all pairs whose first element is a
1757  string -- in this case, the initializer list constructor would create an
1758  object, taking the first elements as keys
1759  2. creating an empty array -- passing the empty initializer list to the
1760  initializer list constructor yields an empty object
1761 
1762  @param[in] init initializer list with JSON values to create an array from
1763  (optional)
1764 
1765  @return JSON array value
1766 
1767  @complexity Linear in the size of @a init.
1768 
1769  @liveexample{The following code shows an example for the `array`
1770  function.,array}
1771 
1772  @sa @ref basic_json(std::initializer_list<basic_json>, bool, value_t) --
1773  create a JSON value from an initializer list
1774  @sa @ref object(std::initializer_list<basic_json>) -- create a JSON object
1775  value from an initializer list
1776 
1777  @since version 1.0.0
1778  */
1779  static basic_json array(std::initializer_list<basic_json> init =
1780  std::initializer_list<basic_json>())
1781  {
1782  return basic_json(init, false, value_t::array);
1783  }
1784 
1785  /*!
1786  @brief explicitly create an object from an initializer list
1787 
1788  Creates a JSON object value from a given initializer list. The initializer
1789  lists elements must be pairs, and their first elements must be strings. If
1790  the initializer list is empty, the empty object `{}` is created.
1791 
1792  @note This function is only added for symmetry reasons. In contrast to the
1793  related function @ref array(std::initializer_list<basic_json>), there are
1794  no cases which can only be expressed by this function. That is, any
1795  initializer list @a init can also be passed to the initializer list

1797  value_t).
1798 
1799  @param[in] init initializer list to create an object from (optional)
1800 
1801  @return JSON object value
1802 
1803  @throw std::domain_error if @a init is not a pair whose first elements are
1804  strings; thrown by
1805  @ref basic_json(std::initializer_list<basic_json>, bool, value_t)

1807  @complexity Linear in the size of @a init.

1810  function.,object}
1811 
1812  @sa @ref basic_json(std::initializer_list<basic_json>, bool, value_t) --
1813  create a JSON value from an initializer list
1814  @sa @ref array(std::initializer_list<basic_json>) -- create a JSON array
1815  value from an initializer list
1816 
1817  @since version 1.0.0
1818  */
1819  static basic_json object(std::initializer_list<basic_json> init =
1820  std::initializer_list<basic_json>())
1821  {
1822  return basic_json(init, false, value_t::object);
1823  }
1824 
1825  /*!
1826  @brief construct an array with count copies of given value
1827 
1828  Constructs a JSON array value by creating @a cnt copies of a passed value.
1829  In case @a cnt is `0`, an empty array is created. As postcondition,
1830  `std::distance(begin(),end()) == cnt` holds.
1831 
1832  @param[in] cnt the number of JSON copies of @a val to create
1833  @param[in] val the JSON value to copy

1839  constructor.,basic_json__size_type_basic_json}

1842  */
1843  basic_json(size_type cnt, const basic_json& val)
1844  : m_type(value_t::array)
1845  {

1847  assert_invariant();
1848  }
1849 
1850  /*!
1851  @brief construct a JSON container given an iterator range
1852 
1853  Constructs the JSON value with the contents of the range `[first, last)`.
1854  The semantics depends on the different types a JSON value can have:
1855  - In case of primitive types (number, boolean, or string), @a first must
1856  be `begin()` and @a last must be `end()`. In this case, the value is
1857  copied. Otherwise, std::out_of_range is thrown.
1858  - In case of structured types (array, object), the constructor behaves as
1859  similar versions for `std::vector`.
1860  - In case of a null type, std::domain_error is thrown.
1861 
1862  @tparam InputIT an input iterator type (@ref iterator or @ref
1863  const_iterator)
1864 
1865  @param[in] first begin of the range to copy from (included)
1866  @param[in] last end of the range to copy from (excluded)
1867 
1868  @pre Iterators @a first and @a last must be initialized. **This
1869  precondition is enforced with an assertion.**
1870 
1871  @throw std::domain_error if iterators are not compatible; that is, do not
1872  belong to the same JSON value; example: `"iterators are not compatible"`
1873  @throw std::out_of_range if iterators are for a primitive type (number,
1874  boolean, or string) where an out of range error can be detected easily;
1875  example: `"iterators out of range"`
1876  @throw std::bad_alloc if allocation for object, array, or string fails
1877  @throw std::domain_error if called with a null value; example: `"cannot
1878  use construct with iterators from null"`
1879 
1880  @complexity Linear in distance between @a first and @a last.
1881 
1882  @liveexample{The example below shows several ways to create JSON values by
1883  specifying a subrange with iterators.,basic_json__InputIt_InputIt}
1884 
1885  @since version 1.0.0
1886  */
1887  template<class InputIT, typename std::enable_if<
1888  std::is_same<InputIT, typename basic_json_t::iterator>::value or
1889  std::is_same<InputIT, typename basic_json_t::const_iterator>::value, int>::type = 0>
1890  basic_json(InputIT first, InputIT last)
1891  {
1892  assert(first.m_object != nullptr);
1893  assert(last.m_object != nullptr);
1894 
1895  // make sure iterator fits the current value
1896  if (first.m_object != last.m_object)
1897  {
1898  throw std::domain_error("iterators are not compatible");
1899  }
1900 
1901  // copy type from first iterator
1902  m_type = first.m_object->m_type;
1903 
1904  // check if iterator range is complete for primitive values
1905  switch (m_type)
1906  {
1907  case value_t::boolean:
1908  case value_t::number_float:
1909  case value_t::number_integer:
1910  case value_t::number_unsigned:
1911  case value_t::string:
1912  {
1913  if (not first.m_it.primitive_iterator.is_begin() or not last.m_it.primitive_iterator.is_end())
1914  {
1915  throw std::out_of_range("iterators out of range");
1916  }
1917  break;
1918  }
1919 
1920  default:
1921  {
1922  break;
1923  }
1924  }
1925 
1926  switch (m_type)
1927  {
1928  case value_t::number_integer:
1929  {
1930  m_value.number_integer = first.m_object->m_value.number_integer;
1931  break;
1932  }
1933 
1934  case value_t::number_unsigned:
1935  {
1936  m_value.number_unsigned = first.m_object->m_value.number_unsigned;
1937  break;
1938  }
1939 
1940  case value_t::number_float:
1941  {
1942  m_value.number_float = first.m_object->m_value.number_float;
1943  break;
1944  }
1945 
1946  case value_t::boolean:
1947  {
1948  m_value.boolean = first.m_object->m_value.boolean;
1949  break;
1950  }
1951 
1952  case value_t::string:
1953  {
1954  m_value = *first.m_object->m_value.string;
1955  break;
1956  }
1957 
1958  case value_t::object:
1959  {
1960  m_value.object = create<object_t>(first.m_it.object_iterator,
1961  last.m_it.object_iterator);
1962  break;
1963  }
1964 
1965  case value_t::array:
1966  {
1967  m_value.array = create<array_t>(first.m_it.array_iterator,
1968  last.m_it.array_iterator);
1969  break;
1970  }
1971 
1972  default:
1973  {
1974  throw std::domain_error("cannot use construct with iterators from " + first.m_object->type_name());
1975  }
1976  }
1977 
1978  assert_invariant();
1979  }
1980 
1981  /*!
1982  @brief construct a JSON value given an input stream
1983 
1984  @param[in,out] i stream to read a serialized JSON value from
1985  @param[in] cb a parser callback function of type @ref parser_callback_t
1986  which is used to control the deserialization by filtering unwanted values
1987  (optional)
1988 
1989  @complexity Linear in the length of the input. The parser is a predictive
1990  LL(1) parser. The complexity can be higher if the parser callback function
1991  @a cb has a super-linear complexity.
1992 
1993  @note A UTF-8 byte order mark is silently ignored.
1994 
1995  @deprecated This constructor is deprecated and will be removed in version
1996  3.0.0 to unify the interface of the library. Deserialization will be
1997  done by stream operators or by calling one of the `parse` functions,
1998  e.g. @ref parse(std::istream&, const parser_callback_t). That is, calls
1999  like `json j(i);` for an input stream @a i need to be replaced by
2000  `json j = json::parse(i);`. See the example below.
2001 
2002  @liveexample{The example below demonstrates constructing a JSON value from
2003  a `std::stringstream` with and without callback
2004  function.,basic_json__istream}
2005 
2006  @since version 2.0.0, deprecated in version 2.0.3, to be removed in
2007  version 3.0.0
2008  */
2009  JSON_DEPRECATED
2010  explicit basic_json(std::istream& i, const parser_callback_t cb = nullptr)
2011  {
2012  *this = parser(i, cb).parse();
2013  assert_invariant();
2014  }
2015

2018  ///////////////////////////////////////

2020  /*!
2021  @brief copy constructor
2022 
2023  Creates a copy of a given JSON value.
2024 
2025  @param[in] other the JSON value to copy
2026 
2027  @complexity Linear in the size of @a other.
2028 
2029  @requirement This function helps `basic_json` satisfying the
2030  [Container](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/concept/Container)
2031  requirements:
2032  - The complexity is linear.
2033  - As postcondition, it holds: `other == basic_json(other)`.
2034 
2035  @throw std::bad_alloc if allocation for object, array, or string fails.
2036 
2037  @liveexample{The following code shows an example for the copy
2038  constructor.,basic_json__basic_json}
2039 
2040  @since version 1.0.0
2041  */
2042  basic_json(const basic_json& other)
2043  : m_type(other.m_type)
2044  {
2045  // check of passed value is valid
2046  other.assert_invariant();
2047 
2048  switch (m_type)
2049  {
2050  case value_t::object:
2051  {
2052  m_value = *other.m_value.object;
2053  break;
2054  }
2055 
2056  case value_t::array:
2057  {
2058  m_value = *other.m_value.array;
2059  break;
2060  }
2061 
2062  case value_t::string:
2063  {
2064  m_value = *other.m_value.string;
2065  break;
2066  }
2067 
2068  case value_t::boolean:
2069  {
2070  m_value = other.m_value.boolean;
2071  break;
2072  }
2073 
2074  case value_t::number_integer:
2075  {
2076  m_value = other.m_value.number_integer;
2077  break;
2078  }
2079 
2080  case value_t::number_unsigned:
2081  {
2082  m_value = other.m_value.number_unsigned;
2083  break;
2084  }
2085 
2086  case value_t::number_float:
2087  {
2088  m_value = other.m_value.number_float;
2089  break;
2090  }
2091 
2092  default:
2093  {
2094  break;
2095  }
2096  }
2097 
2098  assert_invariant();
2099  }

2101  /*!
2102  @brief move constructor
2103 
2104  Move constructor. Constructs a JSON value with the contents of the given
2105  value @a other using move semantics. It "steals" the resources from @a
2106  other and leaves it as JSON null value.
2107 
2108  @param[in,out] other value to move to this object
2109 
2110  @post @a other is a JSON null value
2111 
2112  @complexity Constant.
2113 
2114  @liveexample{The code below shows the move constructor explicitly called
2115  via std::move.,basic_json__moveconstructor}
2116 
2117  @since version 1.0.0
2118  */
2119  basic_json(basic_json&& other) noexcept
2120  : m_type(std::move(other.m_type)),
2121  m_value(std::move(other.m_value))
2122  {
2123  // check that passed value is valid
2124  other.assert_invariant();
2125 
2126  // invalidate payload
2127  other.m_type = value_t::null;
2128  other.m_value = {};
2129 
2130  assert_invariant();
2131  }
2132 
2133  /*!
2134  @brief copy assignment
2135 
2136  Copy assignment operator. Copies a JSON value via the "copy and swap"
2137  strategy: It is expressed in terms of the copy constructor, destructor,
2138  and the swap() member function.
2139 
2140  @param[in] other value to copy from
2141 
2142  @complexity Linear.
2143 
2144  @requirement This function helps `basic_json` satisfying the
2145  [Container](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/concept/Container)
2146  requirements:
2147  - The complexity is linear.
2148 
2149  @liveexample{The code below shows and example for the copy assignment. It
2150  creates a copy of value `a` which is then swapped with `b`. Finally\, the
2151  copy of `a` (which is the null value after the swap) is
2152  destroyed.,basic_json__copyassignment}
2153 
2154  @since version 1.0.0
2155  */
2156  reference& operator=(basic_json other) noexcept (
2157  std::is_nothrow_move_constructible<value_t>::value and
2158  std::is_nothrow_move_assignable<value_t>::value and
2159  std::is_nothrow_move_constructible<json_value>::value and
2160  std::is_nothrow_move_assignable<json_value>::value
2161  )
2162  {
2163  // check that passed value is valid
2164  other.assert_invariant();
2165 
2166  using std::swap;
2167  swap(m_type, other.m_type);
2168  swap(m_value, other.m_value);
2169 
2170  assert_invariant();
2171  return *this;
2172  }
2173 
2174  /*!
2175  @brief destructor
2176 
2177  Destroys the JSON value and frees all allocated memory.
2178 
2179  @complexity Linear.
2180 
2181  @requirement This function helps `basic_json` satisfying the
2182  [Container](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/concept/Container)
2183  requirements:
2184  - The complexity is linear.
2185  - All stored elements are destroyed and all memory is freed.
2186 
2187  @since version 1.0.0
2188  */
2189  ~basic_json()
2190  {
2191  assert_invariant();
2192 
2193  switch (m_type)
2194  {
2195  case value_t::object:
2196  {
2197  AllocatorType<object_t> alloc;
2198  alloc.destroy(m_value.object);
2199  alloc.deallocate(m_value.object, 1);
2200  break;
2201  }
2202 
2203  case value_t::array:
2204  {
2205  AllocatorType<array_t> alloc;
2206  alloc.destroy(m_value.array);
2207  alloc.deallocate(m_value.array, 1);
2208  break;
2209  }
2210 
2211  case value_t::string:
2212  {
2213  AllocatorType<string_t> alloc;
2214  alloc.destroy(m_value.string);
2215  alloc.deallocate(m_value.string, 1);
2216  break;
2217  }
2218 
2219  default:
2220  {
2221  // all other types need no specific destructor
2222  break;
2223  }
2224  }
2225  }

2238  /*!
2239  @brief serialization
2240 
2241  Serialization function for JSON values. The function tries to mimic
2242  Python's `json.dumps()` function, and currently supports its @a indent
2243  parameter.
2244 
2245  @param[in] indent If indent is nonnegative, then array elements and object
2246  members will be pretty-printed with that indent level. An indent level of
2247  `0` will only insert newlines. `-1` (the default) selects the most compact
2248  representation.
2249 
2250  @return string containing the serialization of the JSON value
2251 
2252  @complexity Linear.
2253 
2254  @liveexample{The following example shows the effect of different @a indent
2255  parameters to the result of the serialization.,dump}
2256 
2257  @see https://docs.python.org/2/library/json.html#json.dump
2258 
2259  @since version 1.0.0
2260  */
2261  string_t dump(const int indent = -1) const
2262  {
2263  std::stringstream ss;
2264  // fix locale problems
2265  ss.imbue(std::locale::classic());
2266 
2267  // 6, 15 or 16 digits of precision allows round-trip IEEE 754
2268  // string->float->string, string->double->string or string->long
2269  // double->string; to be safe, we read this value from
2270  // std::numeric_limits<number_float_t>::digits10
2271  ss.precision(std::numeric_limits<double>::digits10);
2272 
2273  if (indent >= 0)
2274  {
2275  dump(ss, true, static_cast<unsigned int>(indent));
2276  }
2277  else
2278  {
2279  dump(ss, false, 0);
2280  }
2281 
2282  return ss.str();
2283  }

2647  /// get an object (explicit)
2648  template<class T, typename std::enable_if<
2649  std::is_convertible<typename object_t::key_type, typename T::key_type>::value and
2650  std::is_convertible<basic_json_t, typename T::mapped_type>::value, int>::type = 0>
2651  T get_impl(T* /*unused*/) const
2652  {
2653  if (is_object())
2654  {
2655  return T(m_value.object->begin(), m_value.object->end());
2656  }
2657 
2658  throw std::domain_error("type must be object, but is " + type_name());
2659  }
2660 
2661  /// get an object (explicit)
2662  object_t get_impl(object_t* /*unused*/) const
2663  {
2664  if (is_object())
2665  {
2666  return *(m_value.object);
2667  }
2668 
2669  throw std::domain_error("type must be object, but is " + type_name());
2670  }

2672  /// get an array (explicit)
2673  template<class T, typename std::enable_if<
2674  std::is_convertible<basic_json_t, typename T::value_type>::value and
2675  not std::is_same<basic_json_t, typename T::value_type>::value and
2676  not std::is_arithmetic<T>::value and
2677  not std::is_convertible<std::string, T>::value and
2678  not has_mapped_type<T>::value, int>::type = 0>
2679  T get_impl(T* /*unused*/) const
2680  {
2681  if (is_array())
2682  {
2683  T to_vector;
2684  std::transform(m_value.array->begin(), m_value.array->end(),
2685  std::inserter(to_vector, to_vector.end()), [](basic_json i)
2686  {
2687  return i.get<typename T::value_type>();
2688  });
2689  return to_vector;
2690  }
2691 
2692  throw std::domain_error("type must be array, but is " + type_name());
2693  }
2694

2696  template<class T, typename std::enable_if<
2697  std::is_convertible<basic_json_t, T>::value and
2698  not std::is_same<basic_json_t, T>::value, int>::type = 0>
2699  std::vector<T> get_impl(std::vector<T>* /*unused*/) const
2700  {
2701  if (is_array())
2702  {
2703  std::vector<T> to_vector;
2704  to_vector.reserve(m_value.array->size());
2705  std::transform(m_value.array->begin(), m_value.array->end(),
2706  std::inserter(to_vector, to_vector.end()), [](basic_json i)
2707  {
2708  return i.get<T>();
2709  });
2710  return to_vector;
2711  }
2712 
2713  throw std::domain_error("type must be array, but is " + type_name());
2714  }

2875  /*!
2876  @brief helper function to implement get_ref()
2877 
2878  This funcion helps to implement get_ref() without code duplication for
2879  const and non-const overloads
2880 
2881  @tparam ThisType will be deduced as `basic_json` or `const basic_json`
2882 
2883  @throw std::domain_error if ReferenceType does not match underlying value
2884  type of the current JSON
2885  */
2886  template<typename ReferenceType, typename ThisType>
2887  static ReferenceType get_ref_impl(ThisType& obj)
2888  {
2889  // helper type
2890  using PointerType = typename std::add_pointer<ReferenceType>::type;
2891 
2892  // delegate the call to get_ptr<>()
2893  auto ptr = obj.template get_ptr<PointerType>();
2894 
2895  if (ptr != nullptr)
2896  {
2897  return *ptr;
2898  }
2899 
2900  throw std::domain_error("incompatible ReferenceType for get_ref, actual type is " +
2901  obj.type_name());
2902  }
2903 
2904  public:
2905 
2906  /// @name value access
2907  /// Direct access to the stored value of a JSON value.
2908  /// @{
2909 
2910  /*!
2911  @brief get a value (explicit)
2912 
2913  Explicit type conversion between the JSON value and a compatible value.
2914 
2915  @tparam ValueType non-pointer type compatible to the JSON value, for
2916  instance `int` for JSON integer numbers, `bool` for JSON booleans, or
2917  `std::vector` types for JSON arrays
2918 
2919  @return copy of the JSON value, converted to type @a ValueType
2920 
2921  @throw std::domain_error in case passed type @a ValueType is incompatible
2922  to JSON; example: `"type must be object, but is null"`
2923 
2924  @complexity Linear in the size of the JSON value.
2925 
2926  @liveexample{The example below shows several conversions from JSON values
2927  to other types. There a few things to note: (1) Floating-point numbers can
2928  be converted to integers\, (2) A JSON array can be converted to a standard
2929  `std::vector<short>`\, (3) A JSON object can be converted to C++
2930  associative containers such as `std::unordered_map<std::string\,
2931  json>`.,get__ValueType_const}
2932 
2933  @internal
2934  The idea of using a casted null pointer to choose the correct
2935  implementation is from <http://stackoverflow.com/a/8315197/266378>.
2936  @endinternal
2937 
2938  @sa @ref operator ValueType() const for implicit conversion
2939  @sa @ref get() for pointer-member access
2940 
2941  @since version 1.0.0
2942  */
2943  template<typename ValueType, typename std::enable_if<
2944  not std::is_pointer<ValueType>::value, int>::type = 0>
2945  ValueType get() const
2946  {
2947  return get_impl(static_cast<ValueType*>(nullptr));
2948  }
2949 
2950  /*!
2951  @brief get a pointer value (explicit)
2952 
2953  Explicit pointer access to the internally stored JSON value. No copies are
2954  made.
2955 
2956  @warning The pointer becomes invalid if the underlying JSON object
2957  changes.
2958 
2959  @tparam PointerType pointer type; must be a pointer to @ref array_t, @ref
2960  object_t, @ref string_t, @ref boolean_t, @ref number_integer_t,
2961  @ref number_unsigned_t, or @ref number_float_t.
2962 
2963  @return pointer to the internally stored JSON value if the requested
2964  pointer type @a PointerType fits to the JSON value; `nullptr` otherwise
2965 
2966  @complexity Constant.
2967 
2968  @liveexample{The example below shows how pointers to internal values of a
2969  JSON value can be requested. Note that no type conversions are made and a
2970  `nullptr` is returned if the value and the requested pointer type does not
2971  match.,get__PointerType}

2974 
2975  @since version 1.0.0
2976  */
2977  template<typename PointerType, typename std::enable_if<
2978  std::is_pointer<PointerType>::value, int>::type = 0>

2997  /*!
2998  @brief get a pointer value (implicit)
2999 
3000  Implicit pointer access to the internally stored JSON value. No copies are
3001  made.
3002 
3003  @warning Writing data to the pointee of the result yields an undefined
3004  state.
3005 
3006  @tparam PointerType pointer type; must be a pointer to @ref array_t, @ref
3007  object_t, @ref string_t, @ref boolean_t, @ref number_integer_t,
3008  @ref number_unsigned_t, or @ref number_float_t. Enforced by a static
3009  assertion.
3010 
3011  @return pointer to the internally stored JSON value if the requested
3012  pointer type @a PointerType fits to the JSON value; `nullptr` otherwise
3013 
3014  @complexity Constant.
3015 
3016  @liveexample{The example below shows how pointers to internal values of a
3017  JSON value can be requested. Note that no type conversions are made and a
3018  `nullptr` is returned if the value and the requested pointer type does not
3019  match.,get_ptr}
3020 
3021  @since version 1.0.0
3022  */
3023  template<typename PointerType, typename std::enable_if<
3024  std::is_pointer<PointerType>::value, int>::type = 0>
3025  PointerType get_ptr() noexcept
3026  {
3027  // get the type of the PointerType (remove pointer and const)
3028  using pointee_t = typename std::remove_const<typename
3029  std::remove_pointer<typename
3030  std::remove_const<PointerType>::type>::type>::type;
3031  // make sure the type matches the allowed types
3032  static_assert(
3033  std::is_same<object_t, pointee_t>::value
3034  or std::is_same<array_t, pointee_t>::value
3035  or std::is_same<string_t, pointee_t>::value
3036  or std::is_same<boolean_t, pointee_t>::value
3037  or std::is_same<number_integer_t, pointee_t>::value
3038  or std::is_same<number_unsigned_t, pointee_t>::value
3039  or std::is_same<number_float_t, pointee_t>::value
3040  , "incompatible pointer type");
3041 
3042  // delegate the call to get_impl_ptr<>()
3043  return get_impl_ptr(static_cast<PointerType>(nullptr));
3044  }
3045 
3046  /*!
3047  @brief get a pointer value (implicit)
3048  @copydoc get_ptr()
3049  */
3050  template<typename PointerType, typename std::enable_if<
3051  std::is_pointer<PointerType>::value and
3052  std::is_const<typename std::remove_pointer<PointerType>::type>::value, int>::type = 0>
3053  constexpr const PointerType get_ptr() const noexcept
3054  {
3055  // get the type of the PointerType (remove pointer and const)
3056  using pointee_t = typename std::remove_const<typename
3057  std::remove_pointer<typename
3058  std::remove_const<PointerType>::type>::type>::type;
3059  // make sure the type matches the allowed types
3060  static_assert(
3061  std::is_same<object_t, pointee_t>::value
3062  or std::is_same<array_t, pointee_t>::value
3063  or std::is_same<string_t, pointee_t>::value
3064  or std::is_same<boolean_t, pointee_t>::value
3065  or std::is_same<number_integer_t, pointee_t>::value
3066  or std::is_same<number_unsigned_t, pointee_t>::value
3067  or std::is_same<number_float_t, pointee_t>::value
3068  , "incompatible pointer type");
3069

3121  /*!

3125  The call is realized by calling @ref get() const.

3129  `std::vector` types for JSON arrays. The character type of @ref string_t
3130  as well as an initializer list of this type is excluded to avoid
3131  ambiguities as these types implicitly convert to `std::string`.
3132

3141  to other types. There a few things to note: (1) Floating-point numbers can
3142  be converted to integers\, (2) A JSON array can be converted to a standard
3143  `std::vector<short>`\, (3) A JSON object can be converted to C++
3144  associative containers such as `std::unordered_map<std::string\,
3145  json>`.,operator__ValueType}
3146 
3147  @since version 1.0.0
3148  */
3149  template < typename ValueType, typename std::enable_if <
3150  not std::is_pointer<ValueType>::value and
3151  not std::is_same<ValueType, typename string_t::value_type>::value
3152 #ifndef _MSC_VER // fix for issue #167 operator<< abiguity under VS2015
3153  and not std::is_same<ValueType, std::initializer_list<typename string_t::value_type>>::value
3154 #endif
3155  , int >::type = 0 >

3157  {

3159  return get<ValueType>();

3170  /// Access to the JSON value.

3173  /*!
3174  @brief access specified array element with bounds checking
3175 
3176  Returns a reference to the element at specified location @a idx, with
3177  bounds checking.
3178 
3179  @param[in] idx index of the element to access
3180 
3181  @return reference to the element at index @a idx
3182 
3183  @throw std::domain_error if the JSON value is not an array; example:
3184  `"cannot use at() with string"`
3185  @throw std::out_of_range if the index @a idx is out of range of the array;
3186  that is, `idx >= size()`; example: `"array index 7 is out of range"`
3187 
3188  @complexity Constant.
3189 
3190  @liveexample{The example below shows how array elements can be read and
3191  written using `at()`.,at__size_type}
3192 
3193  @since version 1.0.0
3194  */
3195  reference at(size_type idx)
3196  {
3197  // at only works for arrays
3198  if (is_array())
3199  {
3200  try
3201  {
3202  return m_value.array->at(idx);
3203  }
3204  catch (std::out_of_range&)
3205  {
3206  // create better exception explanation
3207  throw std::out_of_range("array index " + std::to_string(idx) + " is out of range");
3208  }
3209  }
3210  else
3211  {
3212  throw std::domain_error("cannot use at() with " + type_name());
3213  }
3214  }

3277  written using `at()`.,at__object_t_key_type}

3279  @sa @ref operator[](const typename object_t::key_type&) for unchecked
3280  access by reference
3281  @sa @ref value() for access by value with a default value
3282

3284  */
3285  reference at(const typename object_t::key_type& key)
3286  {
3287  // at only works for objects
3288  if (is_object())
3289  {
3290  try
3291  {
3292  return m_value.object->at(key);
3293  }
3294  catch (std::out_of_range&)
3295  {
3296  // create better exception explanation
3297  throw std::out_of_range("key '" + key + "' not found");
3298  }
3299  }
3300  else
3301  {
3302  throw std::domain_error("cannot use at() with " + type_name());
3303  }
3304  }

3310  with bounds checking.

3353  /*!
3354  @brief access specified array element
3355 
3356  Returns a reference to the element at specified location @a idx.
3357 
3358  @note If @a idx is beyond the range of the array (i.e., `idx >= size()`),
3359  then the array is silently filled up with `null` values to make `idx` a
3360  valid reference to the last stored element.
3361 
3362  @param[in] idx index of the element to access
3363 
3364  @return reference to the element at index @a idx
3365 
3366  @throw std::domain_error if JSON is not an array or null; example:
3367  `"cannot use operator[] with string"`
3368 
3369  @complexity Constant if @a idx is in the range of the array. Otherwise
3370  linear in `idx - size()`.
3371 
3372  @liveexample{The example below shows how array elements can be read and
3373  written using `[]` operator. Note the addition of `null`
3374  values.,operatorarray__size_type}
3375 
3376  @since version 1.0.0
3377  */
3378  reference operator[](size_type idx)
3379  {
3380  // implicitly convert null value to an empty array
3381  if (is_null())
3382  {
3383  m_type = value_t::array;
3384  m_value.array = create<array_t>();
3385  assert_invariant();
3386  }
3387 
3388  // operator[] only works for arrays
3389  if (is_array())
3390  {
3391  // fill up array with null values if given idx is outside range
3392  if (idx >= m_value.array->size())
3393  {
3394  m_value.array->insert(m_value.array->end(),
3395  idx - m_value.array->size() + 1,
3396  basic_json());
3397  }
3398 
3399  return m_value.array->operator[](idx);
3400  }
3401 
3402  throw std::domain_error("cannot use operator[] with " + type_name());
3403  }
