3681  /*!
3682  @brief access specified object element with default value
3683 
3684  Returns either a copy of an object's element at the specified key @a key
3685  or a given default value if no element with key @a key exists.
3686 
3687  The function is basically equivalent to executing
3688  @code {.cpp}
3689  try {
3690  return at(key);
3691  } catch(std::out_of_range) {
3692  return default_value;
3693  }
3694  @endcode
3695 
3696  @note Unlike @ref at(const typename object_t::key_type&), this function
3697  does not throw if the given key @a key was not found.
3698 
3699  @note Unlike @ref operator[](const typename object_t::key_type& key), this
3700  function does not implicitly add an element to the position defined by @a
3701  key. This function is furthermore also applicable to const objects.
3702 
3703  @param[in] key key of the element to access
3704  @param[in] default_value the value to return if @a key is not found
3705 
3706  @tparam ValueType type compatible to JSON values, for instance `int` for
3707  JSON integer numbers, `bool` for JSON booleans, or `std::vector` types for
3708  JSON arrays. Note the type of the expected value at @a key and the default
3709  value @a default_value must be compatible.
3710 
3711  @return copy of the element at key @a key or @a default_value if @a key
3712  is not found
3713 
3714  @throw std::domain_error if JSON is not an object; example: `"cannot use
3715  value() with null"`
3716 
3717  @complexity Logarithmic in the size of the container.
3718 
3719  @liveexample{The example below shows how object elements can be queried
3720  with a default value.,basic_json__value}
3721 
3722  @sa @ref at(const typename object_t::key_type&) for access by reference
3723  with range checking
3724  @sa @ref operator[](const typename object_t::key_type&) for unchecked
3725  access by reference
3726 
3727  @since version 1.0.0
3728  */
3729  template<class ValueType, typename std::enable_if<
3730  std::is_convertible<basic_json_t, ValueType>::value, int>::type = 0>
3731  ValueType value(const typename object_t::key_type& key, ValueType default_value) const
3732  {
3733  // at only works for objects
3734  if (is_object())
3735  {
3736  // if key is found, return value and given default value otherwise
3737  const auto it = find(key);
3738  if (it != end())
3739  {
3740  return *it;
3741  }
3742 
3743  return default_value;
3744  }
3745  else
3746  {
3747  throw std::domain_error("cannot use value() with " + type_name());
3748  }
3749  }

3916  /*!
3917  @brief remove element given an iterator
3918 
3919  Removes the element specified by iterator @a pos. The iterator @a pos must
3920  be valid and dereferenceable. Thus the `end()` iterator (which is valid,
3921  but is not dereferenceable) cannot be used as a value for @a pos.
3922 
3923  If called on a primitive type other than `null`, the resulting JSON value
3924  will be `null`.
3925 
3926  @param[in] pos iterator to the element to remove
3927  @return Iterator following the last removed element. If the iterator @a
3928  pos refers to the last element, the `end()` iterator is returned.
3929 
3930  @tparam IteratorType an @ref iterator or @ref const_iterator
3931 
3932  @post Invalidates iterators and references at or after the point of the
3933  erase, including the `end()` iterator.
3934 
3935  @throw std::domain_error if called on a `null` value; example: `"cannot
3936  use erase() with null"`
3937  @throw std::domain_error if called on an iterator which does not belong to
3938  the current JSON value; example: `"iterator does not fit current value"`
3939  @throw std::out_of_range if called on a primitive type with invalid
3940  iterator (i.e., any iterator which is not `begin()`); example: `"iterator
3941  out of range"`
3942 
3943  @complexity The complexity depends on the type:
3944  - objects: amortized constant
3945  - arrays: linear in distance between pos and the end of the container
3946  - strings: linear in the length of the string
3947  - other types: constant
3948 
3949  @liveexample{The example shows the result of `erase()` for different JSON
3950  types.,erase__IteratorType}
3951 
3952  @sa @ref erase(IteratorType, IteratorType) -- removes the elements in
3953  the given range
3954  @sa @ref erase(const typename object_t::key_type&) -- removes the element
3955  from an object at the given key
3956  @sa @ref erase(const size_type) -- removes the element from an array at
3957  the given index
3958 
3959  @since version 1.0.0
3960  */
3961  template<class IteratorType, typename std::enable_if<
3962  std::is_same<IteratorType, typename basic_json_t::iterator>::value or
3963  std::is_same<IteratorType, typename basic_json_t::const_iterator>::value, int>::type
3964  = 0>
3965  IteratorType erase(IteratorType pos)
3966  {
3967  // make sure iterator fits the current value
3968  if (this != pos.m_object)
3969  {
3970  throw std::domain_error("iterator does not fit current value");
3971  }
3972 
3973  IteratorType result = end();
3974 
3975  switch (m_type)
3976  {
3977  case value_t::boolean:
3978  case value_t::number_float:
3979  case value_t::number_integer:
3980  case value_t::number_unsigned:
3981  case value_t::string:
3982  {
3983  if (not pos.m_it.primitive_iterator.is_begin())
3984  {
3985  throw std::out_of_range("iterator out of range");
3986  }
3987 
3988  if (is_string())
3989  {
3990  AllocatorType<string_t> alloc;
3991  alloc.destroy(m_value.string);
3992  alloc.deallocate(m_value.string, 1);
3993  m_value.string = nullptr;
3994  }
3995 
3996  m_type = value_t::null;
3997  assert_invariant();
3998  break;
3999  }
4000 
4001  case value_t::object:
4002  {
4003  result.m_it.object_iterator = m_value.object->erase(pos.m_it.object_iterator);
4004  break;
4005  }
4006 
4007  case value_t::array:
4008  {
4009  result.m_it.array_iterator = m_value.array->erase(pos.m_it.array_iterator);
4010  break;
4011  }
4012 
4013  default:
4014  {
4015  throw std::domain_error("cannot use erase() with " + type_name());
4016  }
4017  }
4018 
4019  return result;
4020  }
4021 
4022  /*!
4023  @brief remove elements given an iterator range
4024 
4025  Removes the element specified by the range `[first; last)`. The iterator
4026  @a first does not need to be dereferenceable if `first == last`: erasing
4027  an empty range is a no-op.
4028 
4029  If called on a primitive type other than `null`, the resulting JSON value
4030  will be `null`.
4031 
4032  @param[in] first iterator to the beginning of the range to remove
4033  @param[in] last iterator past the end of the range to remove
4034  @return Iterator following the last removed element. If the iterator @a
4035  second refers to the last element, the `end()` iterator is returned.
4036 
4037  @tparam IteratorType an @ref iterator or @ref const_iterator
4038 
4039  @post Invalidates iterators and references at or after the point of the
4040  erase, including the `end()` iterator.
4041 
4042  @throw std::domain_error if called on a `null` value; example: `"cannot
4043  use erase() with null"`
4044  @throw std::domain_error if called on iterators which does not belong to
4045  the current JSON value; example: `"iterators do not fit current value"`
4046  @throw std::out_of_range if called on a primitive type with invalid
4047  iterators (i.e., if `first != begin()` and `last != end()`); example:
4048  `"iterators out of range"`
4049 
4050  @complexity The complexity depends on the type:
4051  - objects: `log(size()) + std::distance(first, last)`
4052  - arrays: linear in the distance between @a first and @a last, plus linear
4053  in the distance between @a last and end of the container
4054  - strings: linear in the length of the string
4055  - other types: constant
4056 
4057  @liveexample{The example shows the result of `erase()` for different JSON
4058  types.,erase__IteratorType_IteratorType}
4059 
4060  @sa @ref erase(IteratorType) -- removes the element at a given position
4061  @sa @ref erase(const typename object_t::key_type&) -- removes the element
4062  from an object at the given key
4063  @sa @ref erase(const size_type) -- removes the element from an array at
4064  the given index
4065 
4066  @since version 1.0.0
4067  */
4068  template<class IteratorType, typename std::enable_if<
4069  std::is_same<IteratorType, typename basic_json_t::iterator>::value or
4070  std::is_same<IteratorType, typename basic_json_t::const_iterator>::value, int>::type
4071  = 0>
4072  IteratorType erase(IteratorType first, IteratorType last)
4073  {
4074  // make sure iterator fits the current value
4075  if (this != first.m_object or this != last.m_object)
4076  {
4077  throw std::domain_error("iterators do not fit current value");
4078  }
4079 
4080  IteratorType result = end();
4081 
4082  switch (m_type)
4083  {
4084  case value_t::boolean:
4085  case value_t::number_float:
4086  case value_t::number_integer:
4087  case value_t::number_unsigned:
4088  case value_t::string:
4089  {
4090  if (not first.m_it.primitive_iterator.is_begin() or not last.m_it.primitive_iterator.is_end())
4091  {
4092  throw std::out_of_range("iterators out of range");
4093  }
4094 
4095  if (is_string())
4096  {
4097  AllocatorType<string_t> alloc;
4098  alloc.destroy(m_value.string);
4099  alloc.deallocate(m_value.string, 1);
4100  m_value.string = nullptr;
4101  }
4102 
4103  m_type = value_t::null;
4104  assert_invariant();
4105  break;
4106  }
4107 
4108  case value_t::object:
4109  {
4110  result.m_it.object_iterator = m_value.object->erase(first.m_it.object_iterator,
4111  last.m_it.object_iterator);
4112  break;
4113  }
4114 
4115  case value_t::array:
4116  {
4117  result.m_it.array_iterator = m_value.array->erase(first.m_it.array_iterator,
4118  last.m_it.array_iterator);
4119  break;
4120  }
4121 
4122  default:
4123  {
4124  throw std::domain_error("cannot use erase() with " + type_name());
4125  }
4126  }
4127 
4128  return result;
4129  }
4130 
4131  /*!
4132  @brief remove element from a JSON object given a key
4133 
4134  Removes elements from a JSON object with the key value @a key.
4135 
4136  @param[in] key value of the elements to remove
4137 
4138  @return Number of elements removed. If @a ObjectType is the default
4139  `std::map` type, the return value will always be `0` (@a key was not
4140  found) or `1` (@a key was found).
4141 
4142  @post References and iterators to the erased elements are invalidated.
4143  Other references and iterators are not affected.
4144 
4145  @throw std::domain_error when called on a type other than JSON object;
4146  example: `"cannot use erase() with null"`
4147 
4148  @complexity `log(size()) + count(key)`
4149 
4150  @liveexample{The example shows the effect of `erase()`.,erase__key_type}
4151 
4152  @sa @ref erase(IteratorType) -- removes the element at a given position
4153  @sa @ref erase(IteratorType, IteratorType) -- removes the elements in
4154  the given range
4155  @sa @ref erase(const size_type) -- removes the element from an array at
4156  the given index
4157 
4158  @since version 1.0.0
4159  */
4160  size_type erase(const typename object_t::key_type& key)
4161  {
4162  // this erase only works for objects
4163  if (is_object())
4164  {
4165  return m_value.object->erase(key);
4166  }
4167 
4168  throw std::domain_error("cannot use erase() with " + type_name());
4169  }
4170 
4171  /*!
4172  @brief remove element from a JSON array given an index
4173 
4174  Removes element from a JSON array at the index @a idx.
4175 
4176  @param[in] idx index of the element to remove
4177 
4178  @throw std::domain_error when called on a type other than JSON array;
4179  example: `"cannot use erase() with null"`
4180  @throw std::out_of_range when `idx >= size()`; example: `"array index 17
4181  is out of range"`
4182 
4183  @complexity Linear in distance between @a idx and the end of the container.
4184 
4185  @liveexample{The example shows the effect of `erase()`.,erase__size_type}
4186 
4187  @sa @ref erase(IteratorType) -- removes the element at a given position
4188  @sa @ref erase(IteratorType, IteratorType) -- removes the elements in
4189  the given range
4190  @sa @ref erase(const typename object_t::key_type&) -- removes the element
4191  from an object at the given key
4192 
4193  @since version 1.0.0
4194  */
4195  void erase(const size_type idx)
4196  {
4197  // this erase only works for arrays
4198  if (is_array())
4199  {
4200  if (idx >= size())
4201  {
4202  throw std::out_of_range("array index " + std::to_string(idx) + " is out of range");
4203  }
4204 
4205  m_value.array->erase(m_value.array->begin() + static_cast<difference_type>(idx));
4206  }
4207  else
4208  {
4209  throw std::domain_error("cannot use erase() with " + type_name());
4210  }
4211  }

4622  /*!
4623  @brief checks whether the container is empty
4624 
4625  Checks if a JSON value has no elements.
4626 
4627  @return The return value depends on the different types and is
4628  defined as follows:
4629  Value type | return value
4630  ----------- | -------------
4631  null | `true`
4632  boolean | `false`
4633  string | `false`
4634  number | `false`
4635  object | result of function `object_t::empty()`
4636  array | result of function `array_t::empty()`
4637 
4638  @note This function does not return whether a string stored as JSON value
4639  is empty - it returns whether the JSON container itself is empty which is
4640  false in the case of a string.
4641 
4642  @complexity Constant, as long as @ref array_t and @ref object_t satisfy
4643  the Container concept; that is, their `empty()` functions have constant
4644  complexity.
4645 
4646  @requirement This function helps `basic_json` satisfying the
4647  [Container](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/concept/Container)
4648  requirements:
4649  - The complexity is constant.
4650  - Has the semantics of `begin() == end()`.
4651 
4652  @liveexample{The following code uses `empty()` to check if a JSON
4653  object contains any elements.,empty}
4654 
4655  @sa @ref size() -- returns the number of elements
4656 
4657  @since version 1.0.0
4658  */
4659  bool empty() const noexcept
4660  {
4661  switch (m_type)
4662  {
4663  case value_t::null:
4664  {
4665  // null values are empty
4666  return true;
4667  }
4668 
4669  case value_t::array:
4670  {
4671  // delegate call to array_t::empty()
4672  return m_value.array->empty();
4673  }
4674 
4675  case value_t::object:
4676  {
4677  // delegate call to object_t::empty()
4678  return m_value.object->empty();
4679  }
4680 
4681  default:
4682  {
4683  // all other types are nonempty
4684  return false;
4685  }
4686  }
4687  }

4689  /*!
4690  @brief returns the number of elements
4691 
4692  Returns the number of elements in a JSON value.
4693 
4694  @return The return value depends on the different types and is
4695  defined as follows:
4696  Value type | return value
4697  ----------- | -------------
4698  null | `0`
4699  boolean | `1`
4700  string | `1`
4701  number | `1`
4702  object | result of function object_t::size()
4703  array | result of function array_t::size()
4704 
4705  @note This function does not return the length of a string stored as JSON
4706  value - it returns the number of elements in the JSON value which is 1 in
4707  the case of a string.
4708 
4709  @complexity Constant, as long as @ref array_t and @ref object_t satisfy
4710  the Container concept; that is, their size() functions have constant
4711  complexity.
4712 
4713  @requirement This function helps `basic_json` satisfying the
4714  [Container](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/concept/Container)
4715  requirements:
4716  - The complexity is constant.
4717  - Has the semantics of `std::distance(begin(), end())`.
4718 
4719  @liveexample{The following code calls `size()` on the different value
4720  types.,size}
4721 
4722  @sa @ref empty() -- checks whether the container is empty
4723  @sa @ref max_size() -- returns the maximal number of elements
4724 
4725  @since version 1.0.0
4726  */
4727  size_type size() const noexcept
4728  {
4729  switch (m_type)
4730  {
4731  case value_t::null:
4732  {
4733  // null values are empty
4734  return 0;
4735  }
4736 
4737  case value_t::array:
4738  {
4739  // delegate call to array_t::size()
4740  return m_value.array->size();
4741  }
4742 
4743  case value_t::object:
4744  {
4745  // delegate call to object_t::size()
4746  return m_value.object->size();
4747  }
4748 
4749  default:
4750  {
4751  // all other types have size 1
4752  return 1;
4753  }
4754  }
4755  }
4756 
4757  /*!
4758  @brief returns the maximum possible number of elements
4759 
4760  Returns the maximum number of elements a JSON value is able to hold due to
4761  system or library implementation limitations, i.e. `std::distance(begin(),
4762  end())` for the JSON value.
4763 
4764  @return The return value depends on the different types and is
4765  defined as follows:
4766  Value type | return value
4767  ----------- | -------------
4768  null | `0` (same as `size()`)
4769  boolean | `1` (same as `size()`)
4770  string | `1` (same as `size()`)
4771  number | `1` (same as `size()`)
4772  object | result of function `object_t::max_size()`
4773  array | result of function `array_t::max_size()`
4774 
4775  @complexity Constant, as long as @ref array_t and @ref object_t satisfy
4776  the Container concept; that is, their `max_size()` functions have constant
4777  complexity.
4778 
4779  @requirement This function helps `basic_json` satisfying the
4780  [Container](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/concept/Container)
4781  requirements:
4782  - The complexity is constant.
4783  - Has the semantics of returning `b.size()` where `b` is the largest
4784  possible JSON value.
4785 
4786  @liveexample{The following code calls `max_size()` on the different value
4787  types. Note the output is implementation specific.,max_size}
4788 
4789  @sa @ref size() -- returns the number of elements
4790 
4791  @since version 1.0.0
4792  */
4793  size_type max_size() const noexcept
4794  {
4795  switch (m_type)
4796  {
4797  case value_t::array:
4798  {
4799  // delegate call to array_t::max_size()
4800  return m_value.array->max_size();
4801  }
4802 
4803  case value_t::object:
4804  {
4805  // delegate call to object_t::max_size()
4806  return m_value.object->max_size();
4807  }
4808 
4809  default:
4810  {
4811  // all other types have max_size() == size()
4812  return size();
4813  }
4814  }
4815  }
4816

4818

4821  // modifiers //
4822  ///////////////

4825  /// @{

4827  /*!
4828  @brief clears the contents
4829 
4830  Clears the content of a JSON value and resets it to the default value as
4831  if @ref basic_json(value_t) would have been called:
4832 
4833  Value type | initial value
4834  ----------- | -------------
4835  null | `null`
4836  boolean | `false`
4837  string | `""`
4838  number | `0`
4839  object | `{}`
4840  array | `[]`
4841 
4842  @complexity Linear in the size of the JSON value.
4843 
4844  @liveexample{The example below shows the effect of `clear()` to different
4845  JSON types.,clear}
4846 
4847  @since version 1.0.0
4848  */
4849  void clear() noexcept
4850  {
4851  switch (m_type)
4852  {
4853  case value_t::number_integer:
4854  {
4855  m_value.number_integer = 0;
4856  break;
4857  }
4858 
4859  case value_t::number_unsigned:
4860  {
4861  m_value.number_unsigned = 0;
4862  break;
4863  }
4864 
4865  case value_t::number_float:
4866  {
4867  m_value.number_float = 0.0;
4868  break;
4869  }
4870 
4871  case value_t::boolean:
4872  {
4873  m_value.boolean = false;
4874  break;
4875  }
4876 
4877  case value_t::string:
4878  {
4879  m_value.string->clear();
4880  break;
4881  }
4882 
4883  case value_t::array:
4884  {
4885  m_value.array->clear();
4886  break;
4887  }
4888 
4889  case value_t::object:
4890  {
4891  m_value.object->clear();
4892  break;
4893  }
4894 
4895  default:
4896  {
4897  break;
4898  }
4899  }
4900  }

4902  /*!
4903  @brief add an object to an array
4904 
4905  Appends the given element @a val to the end of the JSON value. If the
4906  function is called on a JSON null value, an empty array is created before
4907  appending @a val.
4908 
4909  @param[in] val the value to add to the JSON array
4910 
4911  @throw std::domain_error when called on a type other than JSON array or
4912  null; example: `"cannot use push_back() with number"`
4913 
4914  @complexity Amortized constant.
4915 
4916  @liveexample{The example shows how `push_back()` and `+=` can be used to
4917  add elements to a JSON array. Note how the `null` value was silently
4918  converted to a JSON array.,push_back}
4919 
4920  @since version 1.0.0
4921  */
4922  void push_back(basic_json&& val)
4923  {
4924  // push_back only works for null objects or arrays
4925  if (not(is_null() or is_array()))
4926  {
4927  throw std::domain_error("cannot use push_back() with " + type_name());
4928  }
4929 
4930  // transform null object into an array
4931  if (is_null())
4932  {
4933  m_type = value_t::array;
4934  m_value = value_t::array;
4935  assert_invariant();
4936  }
4937 
4938  // add element to array (move semantics)
4939  m_value.array->push_back(std::move(val));
4940  // invalidate object
4941  val.m_type = value_t::null;
4942  }
4943

4945  @brief add an object to an array
4946  @copydoc push_back(basic_json&&)
4947  */
4948  reference operator+=(basic_json&& val)
4949  {
4950  push_back(std::move(val));
4951  return *this;
4952  }

5038  /*!
5039  @brief add an object to an object
5040 
5041  This function allows to use `push_back` with an initializer list. In case
5042 
5043  1. the current value is an object,
5044  2. the initializer list @a init contains only two elements, and
5045  3. the first element of @a init is a string,
5046 
5047  @a init is converted into an object element and added using
5048  @ref push_back(const typename object_t::value_type&). Otherwise, @a init
5049  is converted to a JSON value and added using @ref push_back(basic_json&&).
5050 
5051  @param init an initializer list
5052 
5053  @complexity Linear in the size of the initializer list @a init.
5054 
5055  @note This function is required to resolve an ambiguous overload error,
5056  because pairs like `{"key", "value"}` can be both interpreted as
5057  `object_t::value_type` or `std::initializer_list<basic_json>`, see
5058  https://github.com/nlohmann/json/issues/235 for more information.
5059 
5060  @liveexample{The example shows how initializer lists are treated as
5061  objects when possible.,push_back__initializer_list}
5062  */
5063  void push_back(std::initializer_list<basic_json> init)
5064  {
5065  if (is_object() and init.size() == 2 and init.begin()->is_string())
5066  {
5067  const string_t key = *init.begin();
5068  push_back(typename object_t::value_type(key, *(init.begin() + 1)));
5069  }
5070  else
5071  {
5072  push_back(basic_json(init));
5073  }
5074  }
5075 
5076  /*!
5077  @brief add an object to an object
5078  @copydoc push_back(std::initializer_list<basic_json>)
5079  */
5080  reference operator+=(std::initializer_list<basic_json> init)
5081  {
5082  push_back(init);
5083  return *this;
5084  }

5086  /*!
5087  @brief add an object to an array
5088 
5089  Creates a JSON value from the passed parameters @a args to the end of the
5090  JSON value. If the function is called on a JSON null value, an empty array
5091  is created before appending the value created from @a args.
5092 
5093  @param[in] args arguments to forward to a constructor of @ref basic_json
5094  @tparam Args compatible types to create a @ref basic_json object
5095 
5096  @throw std::domain_error when called on a type other than JSON array or
5097  null; example: `"cannot use emplace_back() with number"`
5098 
5099  @complexity Amortized constant.
5100 
5101  @liveexample{The example shows how `push_back()` can be used to add
5102  elements to a JSON array. Note how the `null` value was silently converted
5103  to a JSON array.,emplace_back}
5104 
5105  @since version 2.0.8
5106  */
5107  template<class... Args>
5108  void emplace_back(Args&& ... args)
5109  {
5110  // emplace_back only works for null objects or arrays
5111  if (not(is_null() or is_array()))
5112  {
5113  throw std::domain_error("cannot use emplace_back() with " + type_name());
5114  }
5115 
5116  // transform null object into an array
5117  if (is_null())
5118  {
5119  m_type = value_t::array;
5120  m_value = value_t::array;
5121  assert_invariant();
5122  }
5123 
5124  // add element to array (perfect forwarding)
5125  m_value.array->emplace_back(std::forward<Args>(args)...);
5126  }
5127 
5128  /*!
5129  @brief add an object to an object if key does not exist
5130 
5131  Inserts a new element into a JSON object constructed in-place with the
5132  given @a args if there is no element with the key in the container. If the
5133  function is called on a JSON null value, an empty object is created before
5134  appending the value created from @a args.
5135 
5136  @param[in] args arguments to forward to a constructor of @ref basic_json
5137  @tparam Args compatible types to create a @ref basic_json object
5138 
5139  @return a pair consisting of an iterator to the inserted element, or the
5140  already-existing element if no insertion happened, and a bool
5141  denoting whether the insertion took place.
5142 
5143  @throw std::domain_error when called on a type other than JSON object or
5144  null; example: `"cannot use emplace() with number"`
5145 
5146  @complexity Logarithmic in the size of the container, O(log(`size()`)).
5147 
5148  @liveexample{The example shows how `emplace()` can be used to add elements
5149  to a JSON object. Note how the `null` value was silently converted to a
5150  JSON object. Further note how no value is added if there was already one
5151  value stored with the same key.,emplace}
5152 
5153  @since version 2.0.8
5154  */
5155  template<class... Args>
5156  std::pair<iterator, bool> emplace(Args&& ... args)
5157  {
5158  // emplace only works for null objects or arrays
5159  if (not(is_null() or is_object()))
5160  {
5161  throw std::domain_error("cannot use emplace() with " + type_name());
5162  }
5163 
5164  // transform null object into an object
5165  if (is_null())
5166  {
5167  m_type = value_t::object;
5168  m_value = value_t::object;
5169  assert_invariant();
5170  }
5171 
5172  // add element to array (perfect forwarding)
5173  auto res = m_value.object->emplace(std::forward<Args>(args)...);
5174  // create result iterator and set iterator to the result of emplace
5175  auto it = begin();
5176  it.m_it.object_iterator = res.first;
5177 
5178  // return pair of iterator and boolean
5179  return {it, res.second};
5180  }

5277  /*!
5278  @brief inserts elements
5279 
5280  Inserts elements from range `[first, last)` before iterator @a pos.
5281 
5282  @param[in] pos iterator before which the content will be inserted; may be
5283  the end() iterator
5284  @param[in] first begin of the range of elements to insert
5285  @param[in] last end of the range of elements to insert
5286 
5287  @throw std::domain_error if called on JSON values other than arrays;
5288  example: `"cannot use insert() with string"`
5289  @throw std::domain_error if @a pos is not an iterator of *this; example:
5290  `"iterator does not fit current value"`
5291  @throw std::domain_error if @a first and @a last do not belong to the same
5292  JSON value; example: `"iterators do not fit"`
5293  @throw std::domain_error if @a first or @a last are iterators into
5294  container for which insert is called; example: `"passed iterators may not
5295  belong to container"`
5296 
5297  @return iterator pointing to the first element inserted, or @a pos if
5298  `first==last`
5299 
5300  @complexity Linear in `std::distance(first, last)` plus linear in the
5301  distance between @a pos and end of the container.
5302 
5303  @liveexample{The example shows how `insert()` is used.,insert__range}
5304 
5305  @since version 1.0.0
5306  */
5307  iterator insert(const_iterator pos, const_iterator first, const_iterator last)
5308  {
5309  // insert only works for arrays
5310  if (not is_array())
5311  {
5312  throw std::domain_error("cannot use insert() with " + type_name());
5313  }
5314 
5315  // check if iterator pos fits to this JSON value
5316  if (pos.m_object != this)
5317  {
5318  throw std::domain_error("iterator does not fit current value");
5319  }
5320 
5321  // check if range iterators belong to the same JSON object
5322  if (first.m_object != last.m_object)
5323  {
5324  throw std::domain_error("iterators do not fit");
5325  }
5326 
5327  if (first.m_object == this or last.m_object == this)
5328  {
5329  throw std::domain_error("passed iterators may not belong to container");
5330  }
5331 
5332  // insert to array and return iterator
5333  iterator result(this);
5334  result.m_it.array_iterator = m_value.array->insert(
5335  pos.m_it.array_iterator,
5336  first.m_it.array_iterator,
5337  last.m_it.array_iterator);
5338  return result;
5339  }

5385  /*!
5386  @brief exchanges the values
5387 
5388  Exchanges the contents of the JSON value with those of @a other. Does not
5389  invoke any move, copy, or swap operations on individual elements. All
5390  iterators and references remain valid. The past-the-end iterator is
5391  invalidated.
5392 
5393  @param[in,out] other JSON value to exchange the contents with
5394 
5395  @complexity Constant.
5396 
5397  @liveexample{The example below shows how JSON values can be swapped with
5398  `swap()`.,swap__reference}
5399 
5400  @since version 1.0.0
5401  */
5402  void swap(reference other) noexcept (
5403  std::is_nothrow_move_constructible<value_t>::value and
5404  std::is_nothrow_move_assignable<value_t>::value and
5405  std::is_nothrow_move_constructible<json_value>::value and
5406  std::is_nothrow_move_assignable<json_value>::value
5407  )
5408  {
5409  std::swap(m_type, other.m_type);
5410  std::swap(m_value, other.m_value);
5411  assert_invariant();
5412  }

5414  /*!
5415  @brief exchanges the values
5416 
5417  Exchanges the contents of a JSON array with those of @a other. Does not
5418  invoke any move, copy, or swap operations on individual elements. All
5419  iterators and references remain valid. The past-the-end iterator is
5420  invalidated.
5421 
5422  @param[in,out] other array to exchange the contents with
5423 
5424  @throw std::domain_error when JSON value is not an array; example:
5425  `"cannot use swap() with string"`
5426 
5427  @complexity Constant.
5428 
5429  @liveexample{The example below shows how arrays can be swapped with
5430  `swap()`.,swap__array_t}
5431 
5432  @since version 1.0.0
5433  */
5434  void swap(array_t& other)
5435  {
5436  // swap only works for arrays
5437  if (is_array())
5438  {
5439  std::swap(*(m_value.array), other);
5440  }
5441  else
5442  {
5443  throw std::domain_error("cannot use swap() with " + type_name());
5444  }
5445  }
5446 
5447  /*!
5448  @brief exchanges the values
5449 
5450  Exchanges the contents of a JSON object with those of @a other. Does not
5451  invoke any move, copy, or swap operations on individual elements. All
5452  iterators and references remain valid. The past-the-end iterator is
5453  invalidated.
5454 
5455  @param[in,out] other object to exchange the contents with
5456 
5457  @throw std::domain_error when JSON value is not an object; example:
5458  `"cannot use swap() with string"`
5459 
5460  @complexity Constant.
5461 
5462  @liveexample{The example below shows how objects can be swapped with
5463  `swap()`.,swap__object_t}
5464 
5465  @since version 1.0.0
5466  */
5467  void swap(object_t& other)
5468  {
5469  // swap only works for objects
5470  if (is_object())
5471  {
5472  std::swap(*(m_value.object), other);
5473  }
5474  else
5475  {
5476  throw std::domain_error("cannot use swap() with " + type_name());
5477  }
5478  }
5479 
5480  /*!
5481  @brief exchanges the values
5482 
5483  Exchanges the contents of a JSON string with those of @a other. Does not
5484  invoke any move, copy, or swap operations on individual elements. All
5485  iterators and references remain valid. The past-the-end iterator is
5486  invalidated.
5487 
5488  @param[in,out] other string to exchange the contents with
5489 
5490  @throw std::domain_error when JSON value is not a string; example: `"cannot
5491  use swap() with boolean"`
5492 
5493  @complexity Constant.
5494 
5495  @liveexample{The example below shows how strings can be swapped with
5496  `swap()`.,swap__string_t}
5497 
5498  @since version 1.0.0
5499  */
5500  void swap(string_t& other)
5501  {
5502  // swap only works for strings
5503  if (is_string())
5504  {
5505  std::swap(*(m_value.string), other);
5506  }
5507  else
5508  {
5509  throw std::domain_error("cannot use swap() with " + type_name());
5510  }
5511  }

5516  //////////////////////////////////////////
5517  // lexicographical comparison operators //
5518  //////////////////////////////////////////
5519 
5520  /// @name lexicographical comparison operators
5521  /// @{
5522 
5523  private:
5524  /*!
5525  @brief comparison operator for JSON types
5526 
5527  Returns an ordering that is similar to Python:
5528  - order: null < boolean < number < object < array < string
5529  - furthermore, each type is not smaller than itself
5530 
5531  @since version 1.0.0
5532  */
5533  friend bool operator<(const value_t lhs, const value_t rhs) noexcept
5534  {
5535  static constexpr std::array<uint8_t, 8> order = {{
5536  0, // null
5537  3, // object
5538  4, // array
5539  5, // string
5540  1, // boolean
5541  2, // integer
5542  2, // unsigned
5543  2, // float
5544  }
5545  };
5546 
5547  // discarded values are not comparable
5548  if (lhs == value_t::discarded or rhs == value_t::discarded)
5549  {
5550  return false;
5551  }
5552 
5553  return order[static_cast<std::size_t>(lhs)] < order[static_cast<std::size_t>(rhs)];
5554  }
5555 
5556  public:
5557  /*!
5558  @brief comparison: equal
5559 
5560  Compares two JSON values for equality according to the following rules:
5561  - Two JSON values are equal if (1) they are from the same type and (2)
5562  their stored values are the same.
5563  - Integer and floating-point numbers are automatically converted before
5564  comparison. Floating-point numbers are compared indirectly: two
5565  floating-point numbers `f1` and `f2` are considered equal if neither
5566  `f1 > f2` nor `f2 > f1` holds.
5567  - Two JSON null values are equal.
5568 
5569  @param[in] lhs first JSON value to consider
5570  @param[in] rhs second JSON value to consider
5571  @return whether the values @a lhs and @a rhs are equal
5572 
5573  @complexity Linear.
5574 
5575  @liveexample{The example demonstrates comparing several JSON
5576  types.,operator__equal}
5577 
5578  @since version 1.0.0
5579  */
5580  friend bool operator==(const_reference lhs, const_reference rhs) noexcept
5581  {
5582  const auto lhs_type = lhs.type();
5583  const auto rhs_type = rhs.type();
5584 
5585  if (lhs_type == rhs_type)
5586  {
5587  switch (lhs_type)
5588  {
5589  case value_t::array:
5590  {
5591  return *lhs.m_value.array == *rhs.m_value.array;
5592  }
5593  case value_t::object:
5594  {
5595  return *lhs.m_value.object == *rhs.m_value.object;
5596  }
5597  case value_t::null:
5598  {
5599  return true;
5600  }
5601  case value_t::string:
5602  {
5603  return *lhs.m_value.string == *rhs.m_value.string;
5604  }
5605  case value_t::boolean:
5606  {
5607  return lhs.m_value.boolean == rhs.m_value.boolean;
5608  }
5609  case value_t::number_integer:
5610  {
5611  return lhs.m_value.number_integer == rhs.m_value.number_integer;
5612  }
5613  case value_t::number_unsigned:
5614  {
5615  return lhs.m_value.number_unsigned == rhs.m_value.number_unsigned;
5616  }
5617  case value_t::number_float:
5618  {
5619  return lhs.m_value.number_float == rhs.m_value.number_float;
5620  }
5621  default:
5622  {
5623  return false;
5624  }
5625  }
5626  }
5627  else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_integer and rhs_type == value_t::number_float)
5628  {
5629  return static_cast<number_float_t>(lhs.m_value.number_integer) == rhs.m_value.number_float;
5630  }
5631  else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_float and rhs_type == value_t::number_integer)
5632  {
5633  return lhs.m_value.number_float == static_cast<number_float_t>(rhs.m_value.number_integer);
5634  }
5635  else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned and rhs_type == value_t::number_float)
5636  {
5637  return static_cast<number_float_t>(lhs.m_value.number_unsigned) == rhs.m_value.number_float;
5638  }
5639  else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_float and rhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned)
5640  {
5641  return lhs.m_value.number_float == static_cast<number_float_t>(rhs.m_value.number_unsigned);
5642  }
5643  else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned and rhs_type == value_t::number_integer)
5644  {
5645  return static_cast<number_integer_t>(lhs.m_value.number_unsigned) == rhs.m_value.number_integer;
5646  }
5647  else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_integer and rhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned)
5648  {
5649  return lhs.m_value.number_integer == static_cast<number_integer_t>(rhs.m_value.number_unsigned);
5650  }
5651 
5652  return false;
5653  }
5654 
5655  /*!
5656  @brief comparison: equal
5657 
5658  The functions compares the given JSON value against a null pointer. As the
5659  null pointer can be used to initialize a JSON value to null, a comparison
5660  of JSON value @a v with a null pointer should be equivalent to call
5661  `v.is_null()`.
5662 
5663  @param[in] v JSON value to consider
5664  @return whether @a v is null
5665 
5666  @complexity Constant.
5667 
5668  @liveexample{The example compares several JSON types to the null pointer.
5669  ,operator__equal__nullptr_t}
5670 
5671  @since version 1.0.0
5672  */
5673  friend bool operator==(const_reference v, std::nullptr_t) noexcept
5674  {
5675  return v.is_null();
5676  }
5677 
5678  /*!
5679  @brief comparison: equal
5680  @copydoc operator==(const_reference, std::nullptr_t)
5681  */
5682  friend bool operator==(std::nullptr_t, const_reference v) noexcept
5683  {
5684  return v.is_null();
5685  }
5686 
5687  /*!
5688  @brief comparison: not equal
5689 
5690  Compares two JSON values for inequality by calculating `not (lhs == rhs)`.
5691 
5692  @param[in] lhs first JSON value to consider
5693  @param[in] rhs second JSON value to consider
5694  @return whether the values @a lhs and @a rhs are not equal
5695 
5696  @complexity Linear.
5697 
5698  @liveexample{The example demonstrates comparing several JSON
5699  types.,operator__notequal}
5700 
5701  @since version 1.0.0
5702  */
5703  friend bool operator!=(const_reference lhs, const_reference rhs) noexcept
5704  {
5705  return not (lhs == rhs);
5706  }
5707 
5708  /*!
5709  @brief comparison: not equal
5710 
5711  The functions compares the given JSON value against a null pointer. As the
5712  null pointer can be used to initialize a JSON value to null, a comparison
5713  of JSON value @a v with a null pointer should be equivalent to call
5714  `not v.is_null()`.
5715 
5716  @param[in] v JSON value to consider
5717  @return whether @a v is not null
5718 
5719  @complexity Constant.
5720 
5721  @liveexample{The example compares several JSON types to the null pointer.
5722  ,operator__notequal__nullptr_t}
5723 
5724  @since version 1.0.0
5725  */
5726  friend bool operator!=(const_reference v, std::nullptr_t) noexcept
5727  {
5728  return not v.is_null();
5729  }
5730 
5731  /*!
5732  @brief comparison: not equal
5733  @copydoc operator!=(const_reference, std::nullptr_t)
5734  */
5735  friend bool operator!=(std::nullptr_t, const_reference v) noexcept
5736  {
5737  return not v.is_null();
5738  }
5739 
5740  /*!
5741  @brief comparison: less than
5742 
5743  Compares whether one JSON value @a lhs is less than another JSON value @a
5744  rhs according to the following rules:
5745  - If @a lhs and @a rhs have the same type, the values are compared using
5746  the default `<` operator.
5747  - Integer and floating-point numbers are automatically converted before
5748  comparison
5749  - In case @a lhs and @a rhs have different types, the values are ignored
5750  and the order of the types is considered, see
5751  @ref operator<(const value_t, const value_t).
5752 
5753  @param[in] lhs first JSON value to consider
5754  @param[in] rhs second JSON value to consider
5755  @return whether @a lhs is less than @a rhs
5756 
5757  @complexity Linear.
5758 
5759  @liveexample{The example demonstrates comparing several JSON
5760  types.,operator__less}
5761 
5762  @since version 1.0.0
5763  */
5764  friend bool operator<(const_reference lhs, const_reference rhs) noexcept
5765  {
5766  const auto lhs_type = lhs.type();
5767  const auto rhs_type = rhs.type();
5768 
5769  if (lhs_type == rhs_type)
5770  {
5771  switch (lhs_type)
5772  {
5773  case value_t::array:
5774  {
5775  return *lhs.m_value.array < *rhs.m_value.array;
5776  }
5777  case value_t::object:
5778  {
5779  return *lhs.m_value.object < *rhs.m_value.object;
5780  }
5781  case value_t::null:
5782  {
5783  return false;
5784  }
5785  case value_t::string:
5786  {
5787  return *lhs.m_value.string < *rhs.m_value.string;
5788  }
5789  case value_t::boolean:
5790  {
5791  return lhs.m_value.boolean < rhs.m_value.boolean;
5792  }
5793  case value_t::number_integer:
5794  {
5795  return lhs.m_value.number_integer < rhs.m_value.number_integer;
5796  }
5797  case value_t::number_unsigned:
5798  {
5799  return lhs.m_value.number_unsigned < rhs.m_value.number_unsigned;
5800  }
5801  case value_t::number_float:
5802  {
5803  return lhs.m_value.number_float < rhs.m_value.number_float;
5804  }
5805  default:
5806  {
5807  return false;
5808  }
5809  }
5810  }
5811  else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_integer and rhs_type == value_t::number_float)
5812  {
5813  return static_cast<number_float_t>(lhs.m_value.number_integer) < rhs.m_value.number_float;
5814  }
5815  else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_float and rhs_type == value_t::number_integer)
5816  {
5817  return lhs.m_value.number_float < static_cast<number_float_t>(rhs.m_value.number_integer);
5818  }
5819  else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned and rhs_type == value_t::number_float)
5820  {
5821  return static_cast<number_float_t>(lhs.m_value.number_unsigned) < rhs.m_value.number_float;
5822  }
5823  else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_float and rhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned)
5824  {
5825  return lhs.m_value.number_float < static_cast<number_float_t>(rhs.m_value.number_unsigned);
5826  }
5827  else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_integer and rhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned)
5828  {
5829  return lhs.m_value.number_integer < static_cast<number_integer_t>(rhs.m_value.number_unsigned);
5830  }
5831  else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned and rhs_type == value_t::number_integer)
5832  {
5833  return static_cast<number_integer_t>(lhs.m_value.number_unsigned) < rhs.m_value.number_integer;
5834  }
5835 
5836  // We only reach this line if we cannot compare values. In that case,
5837  // we compare types. Note we have to call the operator explicitly,
5838  // because MSVC has problems otherwise.
5839  return operator<(lhs_type, rhs_type);
5840  }
5841 
5842  /*!
5843  @brief comparison: less than or equal
5844 
5845  Compares whether one JSON value @a lhs is less than or equal to another
5846  JSON value by calculating `not (rhs < lhs)`.
5847 
5848  @param[in] lhs first JSON value to consider
5849  @param[in] rhs second JSON value to consider
5850  @return whether @a lhs is less than or equal to @a rhs
5851 
5852  @complexity Linear.
5853 
5854  @liveexample{The example demonstrates comparing several JSON
5855  types.,operator__greater}
5856 
5857  @since version 1.0.0
5858  */
5859  friend bool operator<=(const_reference lhs, const_reference rhs) noexcept
5860  {
5861  return not (rhs < lhs);
5862  }
5863 
5864  /*!
5865  @brief comparison: greater than
5866 
5867  Compares whether one JSON value @a lhs is greater than another
5868  JSON value by calculating `not (lhs <= rhs)`.
5869 
5870  @param[in] lhs first JSON value to consider
5871  @param[in] rhs second JSON value to consider
5872  @return whether @a lhs is greater than to @a rhs
5873 
5874  @complexity Linear.
5875 
5876  @liveexample{The example demonstrates comparing several JSON
5877  types.,operator__lessequal}
5878 
5879  @since version 1.0.0
5880  */
5881  friend bool operator>(const_reference lhs, const_reference rhs) noexcept
5882  {
5883  return not (lhs <= rhs);
5884  }
5885 
5886  /*!
5887  @brief comparison: greater than or equal
5888 
5889  Compares whether one JSON value @a lhs is greater than or equal to another
5890  JSON value by calculating `not (lhs < rhs)`.
5891 
5892  @param[in] lhs first JSON value to consider
5893  @param[in] rhs second JSON value to consider
5894  @return whether @a lhs is greater than or equal to @a rhs
5895 
5896  @complexity Linear.
5897 
5898  @liveexample{The example demonstrates comparing several JSON
5899  types.,operator__greaterequal}
5900 
5901  @since version 1.0.0
5902  */
5903  friend bool operator>=(const_reference lhs, const_reference rhs) noexcept
5904  {
5905  return not (lhs < rhs);
5906  }

5910 
5911  ///////////////////
5912  // serialization //
5913  ///////////////////
5914 
5915  /// @name serialization
5916  /// @{
5917 
5918  /*!
5919  @brief serialize to stream
5920 
5921  Serialize the given JSON value @a j to the output stream @a o. The JSON
5922  value will be serialized using the @ref dump member function. The
5923  indentation of the output can be controlled with the member variable
5924  `width` of the output stream @a o. For instance, using the manipulator
5925  `std::setw(4)` on @a o sets the indentation level to `4` and the
5926  serialization result is the same as calling `dump(4)`.
5927 
5928  @note During serializaion, the locale and the precision of the output
5929  stream @a o are changed. The original values are restored when the
5930  function returns.
5931 
5932  @param[in,out] o stream to serialize to
5933  @param[in] j JSON value to serialize
5934 
5935  @return the stream @a o
5936 
5937  @complexity Linear.
5938 
5939  @liveexample{The example below shows the serialization with different
5940  parameters to `width` to adjust the indentation level.,operator_serialize}
5941 
5942  @since version 1.0.0
5943  */
5944  friend std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& o, const basic_json& j)
5945  {
5946  // read width member and use it as indentation parameter if nonzero
5947  const bool pretty_print = (o.width() > 0);
5948  const auto indentation = (pretty_print ? o.width() : 0);
5949 
5950  // reset width to 0 for subsequent calls to this stream
5951  o.width(0);
5952 
5953  // fix locale problems
5954  const auto old_locale = o.imbue(std::locale::classic());
5955  // set precision
5956 
5957  // 6, 15 or 16 digits of precision allows round-trip IEEE 754
5958  // string->float->string, string->double->string or string->long
5959  // double->string; to be safe, we read this value from
5960  // std::numeric_limits<number_float_t>::digits10
5961  const auto old_precision = o.precision(std::numeric_limits<double>::digits10);
5962 
5963  // do the actual serialization
5964  j.dump(o, pretty_print, static_cast<unsigned int>(indentation));
5965 
5966  // reset locale and precision
5967  o.imbue(old_locale);
5968  o.precision(old_precision);
5969  return o;
5970  }
5971 
5972  /*!
5973  @brief serialize to stream
5974  @copydoc operator<<(std::ostream&, const basic_json&)
5975  */
5976  friend std::ostream& operator>>(const basic_json& j, std::ostream& o)
5977  {
5978  return o << j;
5979  }

5985  // deserialization //
5986  /////////////////////
5987 
5988  /// @name deserialization
5989  /// @{
5990 
5991  /*!
5992  @brief deserialize from an array
5993 
5994  This function reads from an array of 1-byte values.
5995 
5996  @pre Each element of the container has a size of 1 byte. Violating this
5997  precondition yields undefined behavior. **This precondition is enforced
5998  with a static assertion.**
5999 
6000  @param[in] array array to read from
6001  @param[in] cb a parser callback function of type @ref parser_callback_t
6002  which is used to control the deserialization by filtering unwanted values
6003  (optional)
6004 
6005  @return result of the deserialization
6006 
6007  @complexity Linear in the length of the input. The parser is a predictive
6008  LL(1) parser. The complexity can be higher if the parser callback function
6009  @a cb has a super-linear complexity.
6010 
6011  @note A UTF-8 byte order mark is silently ignored.
6012 
6013  @liveexample{The example below demonstrates the `parse()` function reading
6014  from an array.,parse__array__parser_callback_t}
6015 
6016  @since version 2.0.3
6017  */
6018  template<class T, std::size_t N>
6019  static basic_json parse(T (&array)[N],
6020  const parser_callback_t cb = nullptr)
6021  {
6022  // delegate the call to the iterator-range parse overload
6023  return parse(std::begin(array), std::end(array), cb);
6024  }
6025 
6026  /*!
6027  @brief deserialize from string literal
6028 
6029  @tparam CharT character/literal type with size of 1 byte
6030  @param[in] s string literal to read a serialized JSON value from
6031  @param[in] cb a parser callback function of type @ref parser_callback_t
6032  which is used to control the deserialization by filtering unwanted values
6033  (optional)
6034 
6035  @return result of the deserialization
6036 
6037  @complexity Linear in the length of the input. The parser is a predictive
6038  LL(1) parser. The complexity can be higher if the parser callback function
6039  @a cb has a super-linear complexity.
6040 
6041  @note A UTF-8 byte order mark is silently ignored.
6042  @note String containers like `std::string` or @ref string_t can be parsed
6043  with @ref parse(const ContiguousContainer&, const parser_callback_t)
6044 
6045  @liveexample{The example below demonstrates the `parse()` function with
6046  and without callback function.,parse__string__parser_callback_t}
6047 
6048  @sa @ref parse(std::istream&, const parser_callback_t) for a version that
6049  reads from an input stream
6050 
6051  @since version 1.0.0 (originally for @ref string_t)
6052  */
6053  template<typename CharT, typename std::enable_if<
6054  std::is_pointer<CharT>::value and
6055  std::is_integral<typename std::remove_pointer<CharT>::type>::value and
6056  sizeof(typename std::remove_pointer<CharT>::type) == 1, int>::type = 0>
6057  static basic_json parse(const CharT s,
6058  const parser_callback_t cb = nullptr)
6059  {
6060  return parser(reinterpret_cast<const char*>(s), cb).parse();
6061  }
6062 
6063  /*!
6064  @brief deserialize from stream
6065 
6066  @param[in,out] i stream to read a serialized JSON value from
6067  @param[in] cb a parser callback function of type @ref parser_callback_t
6068  which is used to control the deserialization by filtering unwanted values
6069  (optional)
6070 
6071  @return result of the deserialization
6072 
6073  @complexity Linear in the length of the input. The parser is a predictive
6074  LL(1) parser. The complexity can be higher if the parser callback function
6075  @a cb has a super-linear complexity.
6076 
6077  @note A UTF-8 byte order mark is silently ignored.
6078 
6079  @liveexample{The example below demonstrates the `parse()` function with
6080  and without callback function.,parse__istream__parser_callback_t}
6081 
6082  @sa @ref parse(const CharT, const parser_callback_t) for a version
6083  that reads from a string
6084 
6085  @since version 1.0.0
6086  */
6087  static basic_json parse(std::istream& i,
6088  const parser_callback_t cb = nullptr)
6089  {
6090  return parser(i, cb).parse();
6091  }
6092 
6093  /*!
6094  @copydoc parse(std::istream&, const parser_callback_t)
6095  */
6096  static basic_json parse(std::istream&& i,
6097  const parser_callback_t cb = nullptr)
6098  {
6099  return parser(i, cb).parse();
6100  }
6101 
6102  /*!
6103  @brief deserialize from an iterator range with contiguous storage
6104 
6105  This function reads from an iterator range of a container with contiguous
6106  storage of 1-byte values. Compatible container types include
6107  `std::vector`, `std::string`, `std::array`, `std::valarray`, and
6108  `std::initializer_list`. Furthermore, C-style arrays can be used with
6109  `std::begin()`/`std::end()`. User-defined containers can be used as long
6110  as they implement random-access iterators and a contiguous storage.
6111 
6112  @pre The iterator range is contiguous. Violating this precondition yields
6113  undefined behavior. **This precondition is enforced with an assertion.**
6114  @pre Each element in the range has a size of 1 byte. Violating this
6115  precondition yields undefined behavior. **This precondition is enforced
6116  with a static assertion.**
6117 
6118  @warning There is no way to enforce all preconditions at compile-time. If
6119  the function is called with noncompliant iterators and with
6120  assertions switched off, the behavior is undefined and will most
6121  likely yield segmentation violation.
6122 
6123  @tparam IteratorType iterator of container with contiguous storage
6124  @param[in] first begin of the range to parse (included)
6125  @param[in] last end of the range to parse (excluded)
6126  @param[in] cb a parser callback function of type @ref parser_callback_t
6127  which is used to control the deserialization by filtering unwanted values
6128  (optional)
6129 
6130  @return result of the deserialization
6131 
6132  @complexity Linear in the length of the input. The parser is a predictive
6133  LL(1) parser. The complexity can be higher if the parser callback function
6134  @a cb has a super-linear complexity.
6135 
6136  @note A UTF-8 byte order mark is silently ignored.
6137 
6138  @liveexample{The example below demonstrates the `parse()` function reading
6139  from an iterator range.,parse__iteratortype__parser_callback_t}
6140 
6141  @since version 2.0.3
6142  */
6143  template<class IteratorType, typename std::enable_if<
6144  std::is_base_of<
6145  std::random_access_iterator_tag,
6146  typename std::iterator_traits<IteratorType>::iterator_category>::value, int>::type = 0>
6147  static basic_json parse(IteratorType first, IteratorType last,
6148  const parser_callback_t cb = nullptr)
6149  {
6150  // assertion to check that the iterator range is indeed contiguous,
6151  // see http://stackoverflow.com/a/35008842/266378 for more discussion
6152  assert(std::accumulate(first, last, std::pair<bool, int>(true, 0),
6153  [&first](std::pair<bool, int> res, decltype(*first) val)
6154  {
6155  res.first &= (val == *(std::next(std::addressof(*first), res.second++)));
6156  return res;
6157  }).first);
6158 
6159  // assertion to check that each element is 1 byte long
6160  static_assert(sizeof(typename std::iterator_traits<IteratorType>::value_type) == 1,
6161  "each element in the iterator range must have the size of 1 byte");
6162 
6163  // if iterator range is empty, create a parser with an empty string
6164  // to generate "unexpected EOF" error message
6165  if (std::distance(first, last) <= 0)
6166  {
6167  return parser("").parse();
6168  }
6169 
6170  return parser(first, last, cb).parse();
6171  }
6172 
6173  /*!
6174  @brief deserialize from a container with contiguous storage
6175 
6176  This function reads from a container with contiguous storage of 1-byte
6177  values. Compatible container types include `std::vector`, `std::string`,
6178  `std::array`, and `std::initializer_list`. User-defined containers can be
6179  used as long as they implement random-access iterators and a contiguous
6180  storage.
6181 
6182  @pre The container storage is contiguous. Violating this precondition
6183  yields undefined behavior. **This precondition is enforced with an
6184  assertion.**
6185  @pre Each element of the container has a size of 1 byte. Violating this
6186  precondition yields undefined behavior. **This precondition is enforced
6187  with a static assertion.**
6188 
6189  @warning There is no way to enforce all preconditions at compile-time. If
6190  the function is called with a noncompliant container and with
6191  assertions switched off, the behavior is undefined and will most
6192  likely yield segmentation violation.
6193 
6194  @tparam ContiguousContainer container type with contiguous storage
6195  @param[in] c container to read from
6196  @param[in] cb a parser callback function of type @ref parser_callback_t
6197  which is used to control the deserialization by filtering unwanted values
6198  (optional)
6199 
6200  @return result of the deserialization
6201 
6202  @complexity Linear in the length of the input. The parser is a predictive
6203  LL(1) parser. The complexity can be higher if the parser callback function
6204  @a cb has a super-linear complexity.
6205 
6206  @note A UTF-8 byte order mark is silently ignored.
6207 
6208  @liveexample{The example below demonstrates the `parse()` function reading
6209  from a contiguous container.,parse__contiguouscontainer__parser_callback_t}
6210 
6211  @since version 2.0.3
6212  */
6213  template<class ContiguousContainer, typename std::enable_if<
6214  not std::is_pointer<ContiguousContainer>::value and
6215  std::is_base_of<
6216  std::random_access_iterator_tag,
6217  typename std::iterator_traits<decltype(std::begin(std::declval<ContiguousContainer const>()))>::iterator_category>::value
6218  , int>::type = 0>
6219  static basic_json parse(const ContiguousContainer& c,
6220  const parser_callback_t cb = nullptr)
6221  {
6222  // delegate the call to the iterator-range parse overload
6223  return parse(std::begin(c), std::end(c), cb);
6224  }

6249  friend std::istream& operator<<(basic_json& j, std::istream& i)
