10179 
10180  /*!
10181  @brief append data from the stream to the line buffer
10182 
10183  This function is called by the scan() function when the end of the
10184  buffer (`m_limit`) is reached and the `m_cursor` pointer cannot be
10185  incremented without leaving the limits of the line buffer. Note re2c
10186  decides when to call this function.
10187 
10188  If the lexer reads from contiguous storage, there is no trailing null
10189  byte. Therefore, this function must make sure to add these padding
10190  null bytes.
10191 
10192  If the lexer reads from an input stream, this function reads the next
10193  line of the input.
10194 
10195  @pre
10196  p p p p p p u u u u u x . . . . . .
10197  ^ ^ ^ ^
10198  m_content m_start | m_limit
10199  m_cursor
10200 
10201  @post
10202  u u u u u x x x x x x x . . . . . .
10203  ^ ^ ^
10204  | m_cursor m_limit
10205  m_start
10206  m_content
10207  */
10208  void fill_line_buffer(size_t n = 0)
10209  {
10210  // if line buffer is used, m_content points to its data
10211  assert(m_line_buffer.empty()
10212  or m_content == reinterpret_cast<const lexer_char_t*>(m_line_buffer.data()));
10213 
10214  // if line buffer is used, m_limit is set past the end of its data
10215  assert(m_line_buffer.empty()
10216  or m_limit == m_content + m_line_buffer.size());
10217 
10218  // pointer relationships
10219  assert(m_content <= m_start);
10220  assert(m_start <= m_cursor);
10221  assert(m_cursor <= m_limit);
10222  assert(m_marker == nullptr or m_marker <= m_limit);
10223 
10224  // number of processed characters (p)
10225  const auto num_processed_chars = static_cast<size_t>(m_start - m_content);
10226  // offset for m_marker wrt. to m_start
10227  const auto offset_marker = (m_marker == nullptr) ? 0 : m_marker - m_start;
10228  // number of unprocessed characters (u)
10229  const auto offset_cursor = m_cursor - m_start;
10230 
10231  // no stream is used or end of file is reached
10232  if (m_stream == nullptr or m_stream->eof())
10233  {
10234  // m_start may or may not be pointing into m_line_buffer at
10235  // this point. We trust the standand library to do the right
10236  // thing. See http://stackoverflow.com/q/28142011/266378
10237  m_line_buffer.assign(m_start, m_limit);
10238 
10239  // append n characters to make sure that there is sufficient
10240  // space between m_cursor and m_limit
10241  m_line_buffer.append(1, '\x00');
10242  if (n > 0)
10243  {
10244  m_line_buffer.append(n - 1, '\x01');
10245  }
10246  }
10247  else
10248  {
10249  // delete processed characters from line buffer
10250  m_line_buffer.erase(0, num_processed_chars);
10251  // read next line from input stream
10252  m_line_buffer_tmp.clear();
10253  std::getline(*m_stream, m_line_buffer_tmp, '\n');
10254 
10255  // add line with newline symbol to the line buffer
10256  m_line_buffer += m_line_buffer_tmp;
10257  m_line_buffer.push_back('\n');
10258  }
10259 
10260  // set pointers
10261  m_content = reinterpret_cast<const lexer_char_t*>(m_line_buffer.data());
10262  assert(m_content != nullptr);
10263  m_start = m_content;
10264  m_marker = m_start + offset_marker;
10265  m_cursor = m_start + offset_cursor;
10266  m_limit = m_start + m_line_buffer.size();
10267  }
10268 
10269  /// return string representation of last read token
10270  string_t get_token_string() const
10271  {
10272  assert(m_start != nullptr);
10273  return string_t(reinterpret_cast<typename string_t::const_pointer>(m_start),
10274  static_cast<size_t>(m_cursor - m_start));
10275  }
10276 
10277  /*!
10278  @brief return string value for string tokens
10279 
10280  The function iterates the characters between the opening and closing
10281  quotes of the string value. The complete string is the range
10282  [m_start,m_cursor). Consequently, we iterate from m_start+1 to
10283  m_cursor-1.
10284 
10285  We differentiate two cases:
10286 
10287  1. Escaped characters. In this case, a new character is constructed
10288  according to the nature of the escape. Some escapes create new
10289  characters (e.g., `"\\n"` is replaced by `"\n"`), some are copied
10290  as is (e.g., `"\\\\"`). Furthermore, Unicode escapes of the shape
10291  `"\\uxxxx"` need special care. In this case, to_unicode takes care
10292  of the construction of the values.
10293  2. Unescaped characters are copied as is.
10294 
10295  @pre `m_cursor - m_start >= 2`, meaning the length of the last token
10296  is at least 2 bytes which is trivially true for any string (which
10297  consists of at least two quotes).
10298 
10299  " c1 c2 c3 ... "
10300  ^ ^
10301  m_start m_cursor
10302 
10303  @complexity Linear in the length of the string.\n
10304 
10305  Lemma: The loop body will always terminate.\n
10306 
10307  Proof (by contradiction): Assume the loop body does not terminate. As
10308  the loop body does not contain another loop, one of the called
10309  functions must never return. The called functions are `std::strtoul`
10310  and to_unicode. Neither function can loop forever, so the loop body
10311  will never loop forever which contradicts the assumption that the loop
10312  body does not terminate, q.e.d.\n
10313 
10314  Lemma: The loop condition for the for loop is eventually false.\n
10315 
10316  Proof (by contradiction): Assume the loop does not terminate. Due to
10317  the above lemma, this can only be due to a tautological loop
10318  condition; that is, the loop condition i < m_cursor - 1 must always be
10319  true. Let x be the change of i for any loop iteration. Then
10320  m_start + 1 + x < m_cursor - 1 must hold to loop indefinitely. This
10321  can be rephrased to m_cursor - m_start - 2 > x. With the
10322  precondition, we x <= 0, meaning that the loop condition holds
10323  indefinitly if i is always decreased. However, observe that the value
10324  of i is strictly increasing with each iteration, as it is incremented
10325  by 1 in the iteration expression and never decremented inside the loop
10326  body. Hence, the loop condition will eventually be false which
10327  contradicts the assumption that the loop condition is a tautology,
10328  q.e.d.
10329 
10330  @return string value of current token without opening and closing
10331  quotes
10332  @throw std::out_of_range if to_unicode fails
10333  */
10334  string_t get_string() const
10335  {
10336  assert(m_cursor - m_start >= 2);
10337 
10338  string_t result;
10339  result.reserve(static_cast<size_t>(m_cursor - m_start - 2));
10340 
10341  // iterate the result between the quotes
10342  for (const lexer_char_t* i = m_start + 1; i < m_cursor - 1; ++i)
10343  {
10344  // find next escape character
10345  auto e = std::find(i, m_cursor - 1, '\\');
10346  if (e != i)
10347  {
10348  // see https://github.com/nlohmann/json/issues/365#issuecomment-262874705
10349  for (auto k = i; k < e; k++)
10350  {
10351  result.push_back(static_cast<typename string_t::value_type>(*k));
10352  }
10353  i = e - 1; // -1 because of ++i
10354  }
10355  else
10356  {
10357  // processing escaped character
10358  // read next character
10359  ++i;
10360 
10361  switch (*i)
10362  {
10363  // the default escapes
10364  case 't':
10365  {
10366  result += "\t";
10367  break;
10368  }
10369  case 'b':
10370  {
10371  result += "\b";
10372  break;
10373  }
10374  case 'f':
10375  {
10376  result += "\f";
10377  break;
10378  }
10379  case 'n':
10380  {
10381  result += "\n";
10382  break;
10383  }
10384  case 'r':
10385  {
10386  result += "\r";
10387  break;
10388  }
10389  case '\\':
10390  {
10391  result += "\\";
10392  break;
10393  }
10394  case '/':
10395  {
10396  result += "/";
10397  break;
10398  }
10399  case '"':
10400  {
10401  result += "\"";
10402  break;
10403  }
10404 
10405  // unicode
10406  case 'u':
10407  {
10408  // get code xxxx from uxxxx
10409  auto codepoint = std::strtoul(std::string(reinterpret_cast<typename string_t::const_pointer>(i + 1),
10410  4).c_str(), nullptr, 16);
10411 
10412  // check if codepoint is a high surrogate
10413  if (codepoint >= 0xD800 and codepoint <= 0xDBFF)
10414  {
10415  // make sure there is a subsequent unicode
10416  if ((i + 6 >= m_limit) or * (i + 5) != '\\' or * (i + 6) != 'u')
10417  {
10418  throw std::invalid_argument("missing low surrogate");
10419  }
10420 
10421  // get code yyyy from uxxxx\uyyyy
10422  auto codepoint2 = std::strtoul(std::string(reinterpret_cast<typename string_t::const_pointer>
10423  (i + 7), 4).c_str(), nullptr, 16);
10424  result += to_unicode(codepoint, codepoint2);
10425  // skip the next 10 characters (xxxx\uyyyy)
10426  i += 10;
10427  }
10428  else if (codepoint >= 0xDC00 and codepoint <= 0xDFFF)
10429  {
10430  // we found a lone low surrogate
10431  throw std::invalid_argument("missing high surrogate");
10432  }
10433  else
10434  {
10435  // add unicode character(s)
10436  result += to_unicode(codepoint);
10437  // skip the next four characters (xxxx)
10438  i += 4;
10439  }
10440  break;
10441  }
10442  }
10443  }
10444  }
10445 
10446  return result;
10447  }
10448 
10449  /*!
10450  @brief parse floating point number
10451 
10452  This function (and its overloads) serves to select the most approprate
10453  standard floating point number parsing function based on the type
10454  supplied via the first parameter. Set this to @a
10455  static_cast<number_float_t*>(nullptr).
10456 
10457  @param[in,out] endptr recieves a pointer to the first character after
10458  the number
10459 
10460  @return the floating point number
10461  */
10462  long double str_to_float_t(long double* /* type */, char** endptr) const
10463  {
10464  return std::strtold(reinterpret_cast<typename string_t::const_pointer>(m_start), endptr);
10465  }
10466 
10467  /*!
10468  @brief parse floating point number
10469 
10470  This function (and its overloads) serves to select the most approprate
10471  standard floating point number parsing function based on the type
10472  supplied via the first parameter. Set this to @a
10473  static_cast<number_float_t*>(nullptr).
10474 
10475  @param[in,out] endptr recieves a pointer to the first character after
10476  the number
10477 
10478  @return the floating point number
10479  */
10480  double str_to_float_t(double* /* type */, char** endptr) const
10481  {
10482  return std::strtod(reinterpret_cast<typename string_t::const_pointer>(m_start), endptr);
10483  }
10484 
10485  /*!
10486  @brief parse floating point number
10487 
10488  This function (and its overloads) serves to select the most approprate
10489  standard floating point number parsing function based on the type
10490  supplied via the first parameter. Set this to @a
10491  static_cast<number_float_t*>(nullptr).
10492 
10493  @param[in,out] endptr recieves a pointer to the first character after
10494  the number
10495 
10496  @return the floating point number
10497  */
10498  float str_to_float_t(float* /* type */, char** endptr) const
10499  {
10500  return std::strtof(reinterpret_cast<typename string_t::const_pointer>(m_start), endptr);
10501  }
10502 
10503  /*!
10504  @brief return number value for number tokens
10505 
10506  This function translates the last token into the most appropriate
10507  number type (either integer, unsigned integer or floating point),
10508  which is passed back to the caller via the result parameter.
10509 
10510  This function parses the integer component up to the radix point or
10511  exponent while collecting information about the 'floating point
10512  representation', which it stores in the result parameter. If there is
10513  no radix point or exponent, and the number can fit into a @ref
10514  number_integer_t or @ref number_unsigned_t then it sets the result
10515  parameter accordingly.
10516 
10517  If the number is a floating point number the number is then parsed
10518  using @a std:strtod (or @a std:strtof or @a std::strtold).
10519 
10520  @param[out] result @ref basic_json object to receive the number, or
10521  NAN if the conversion read past the current token. The latter case
10522  needs to be treated by the caller function.
10523  */
10524  void get_number(basic_json& result) const
10525  {
10526  assert(m_start != nullptr);
10527 
10528  const lexer::lexer_char_t* curptr = m_start;
10529 
10530  // accumulate the integer conversion result (unsigned for now)
10531  number_unsigned_t value = 0;
10532 
10533  // maximum absolute value of the relevant integer type
10534  number_unsigned_t max;
10535 
10536  // temporarily store the type to avoid unecessary bitfield access
10537  value_t type;
10538 
10539  // look for sign
10540  if (*curptr == '-')
10541  {
10542  type = value_t::number_integer;
10543  max = static_cast<uint64_t>((std::numeric_limits<number_integer_t>::max)()) + 1;
10544  curptr++;
10545  }
10546  else
10547  {
10548  type = value_t::number_unsigned;
10549  max = static_cast<uint64_t>((std::numeric_limits<number_unsigned_t>::max)());
10550  }
10551 
10552  // count the significant figures
10553  for (; curptr < m_cursor; curptr++)
10554  {
10555  // quickly skip tests if a digit
10556  if (*curptr < '0' || *curptr > '9')
10557  {
10558  if (*curptr == '.')
10559  {
10560  // don't count '.' but change to float
10561  type = value_t::number_float;
10562  continue;
10563  }
10564  // assume exponent (if not then will fail parse): change to
10565  // float, stop counting and record exponent details
10566  type = value_t::number_float;
10567  break;
10568  }
10569 
10570  // skip if definitely not an integer
10571  if (type != value_t::number_float)
10572  {
10573  auto digit = static_cast<number_unsigned_t>(*curptr - '0');
10574 
10575  // overflow if value * 10 + digit > max, move terms around
10576  // to avoid overflow in intermediate values
10577  if (value > (max - digit) / 10)
10578  {
10579  // overflow
10580  type = value_t::number_float;
10581  }
10582  else
10583  {
10584  // no overflow
10585  value = value * 10 + digit;
10586  }
10587  }
10588  }
10589 
10590  // save the value (if not a float)
10591  if (type == value_t::number_unsigned)
10592  {
10593  result.m_value.number_unsigned = value;
10594  }
10595  else if (type == value_t::number_integer)
10596  {
10597  // invariant: if we parsed a '-', the absolute value is between
10598  // 0 (we allow -0) and max == -INT64_MIN
10599  assert(value >= 0);
10600  assert(value <= max);
10601 
10602  if (value == max)
10603  {
10604  // we cannot simply negate value (== max == -INT64_MIN),
10605  // see https://github.com/nlohmann/json/issues/389
10606  result.m_value.number_integer = static_cast<number_integer_t>(INT64_MIN);
10607  }
10608  else
10609  {
10610  // all other values can be negated safely
10611  result.m_value.number_integer = -static_cast<number_integer_t>(value);
10612  }
10613  }
10614  else
10615  {
10616  // parse with strtod
10617  result.m_value.number_float = str_to_float_t(static_cast<number_float_t*>(nullptr), nullptr);
10618 
10619  // replace infinity and NAN by null
10620  if (not std::isfinite(result.m_value.number_float))
10621  {
10622  type = value_t::null;
10623  result.m_value = basic_json::json_value();
10624  }
10625  }
10626 
10627  // save the type
10628  result.m_type = type;
10629  }
10630 
10631  private:
10632  /// optional input stream
10633  std::istream* m_stream = nullptr;
10634  /// line buffer buffer for m_stream
10635  string_t m_line_buffer {};
10636  /// used for filling m_line_buffer
10637  string_t m_line_buffer_tmp {};
10638  /// the buffer pointer
10639  const lexer_char_t* m_content = nullptr;
10640  /// pointer to the beginning of the current symbol
10641  const lexer_char_t* m_start = nullptr;
10642  /// pointer for backtracking information
10643  const lexer_char_t* m_marker = nullptr;
10644  /// pointer to the current symbol
10645  const lexer_char_t* m_cursor = nullptr;
10646  /// pointer to the end of the buffer
10647  const lexer_char_t* m_limit = nullptr;
10648  /// the last token type
10649  token_type last_token_type = token_type::end_of_input;
10650  };
10651 
10652  /*!
10653  @brief syntax analysis
10654 
10655  This class implements a recursive decent parser.
10656  */
10657  class parser
10658  {
10659  public:
10660  /// a parser reading from a string literal
10661  parser(const char* buff, const parser_callback_t cb = nullptr)
10662  : callback(cb),
10663  m_lexer(reinterpret_cast<const typename lexer::lexer_char_t*>(buff), std::strlen(buff))
10664  {}
10665 
10666  /// a parser reading from an input stream
10667  parser(std::istream& is, const parser_callback_t cb = nullptr)
10668  : callback(cb), m_lexer(is)
10669  {}
10670 
10671  /// a parser reading from an iterator range with contiguous storage
10672  template<class IteratorType, typename std::enable_if<
10673  std::is_same<typename std::iterator_traits<IteratorType>::iterator_category, std::random_access_iterator_tag>::value
10674  , int>::type
10675  = 0>
10676  parser(IteratorType first, IteratorType last, const parser_callback_t cb = nullptr)
10677  : callback(cb),
10678  m_lexer(reinterpret_cast<const typename lexer::lexer_char_t*>(&(*first)),
10679  static_cast<size_t>(std::distance(first, last)))
10680  {}
10681 
10682  /// public parser interface
10683  basic_json parse()
10684  {
10685  // read first token
10686  get_token();
10687 
10688  basic_json result = parse_internal(true);
10689  result.assert_invariant();
10690 
10691  expect(lexer::token_type::end_of_input);
10692 
10693  // return parser result and replace it with null in case the
10694  // top-level value was discarded by the callback function
10695  return result.is_discarded() ? basic_json() : std::move(result);
10696  }
10697 
10698  private:
10699  /// the actual parser
10700  basic_json parse_internal(bool keep)
10701  {
10702  auto result = basic_json(value_t::discarded);
10703 
10704  switch (last_token)
10705  {
10706  case lexer::token_type::begin_object:
10707  {
10708  if (keep and (not callback
10709  or ((keep = callback(depth++, parse_event_t::object_start, result)) != 0)))
10710  {
10711  // explicitly set result to object to cope with {}
10712  result.m_type = value_t::object;
10713  result.m_value = value_t::object;
10714  }
10715 
10716  // read next token
10717  get_token();
10718 
10719  // closing } -> we are done
10720  if (last_token == lexer::token_type::end_object)
10721  {
10722  get_token();
10723  if (keep and callback and not callback(--depth, parse_event_t::object_end, result))
10724  {
10725  result = basic_json(value_t::discarded);
10726  }
10727  return result;
10728  }
10729 
10730  // no comma is expected here
10731  unexpect(lexer::token_type::value_separator);
10732 
10733  // otherwise: parse key-value pairs
10734  do
10735  {
10736  // ugly, but could be fixed with loop reorganization
10737  if (last_token == lexer::token_type::value_separator)
10738  {
10739  get_token();
10740  }
10741 
10742  // store key
10743  expect(lexer::token_type::value_string);
10744  const auto key = m_lexer.get_string();
10745 
10746  bool keep_tag = false;
10747  if (keep)
10748  {
10749  if (callback)
10750  {
10751  basic_json k(key);
10752  keep_tag = callback(depth, parse_event_t::key, k);
10753  }
10754  else
10755  {
10756  keep_tag = true;
10757  }
10758  }
10759 
10760  // parse separator (:)
10761  get_token();
10762  expect(lexer::token_type::name_separator);
10763 
10764  // parse and add value
10765  get_token();
10766  auto value = parse_internal(keep);
10767  if (keep and keep_tag and not value.is_discarded())
10768  {
10769  result[key] = std::move(value);
10770  }
10771  }
10772  while (last_token == lexer::token_type::value_separator);
10773 
10774  // closing }
10775  expect(lexer::token_type::end_object);
10776  get_token();
10777  if (keep and callback and not callback(--depth, parse_event_t::object_end, result))
10778  {
10779  result = basic_json(value_t::discarded);
10780  }
10781 
10782  return result;
10783  }
10784 
10785  case lexer::token_type::begin_array:
10786  {
10787  if (keep and (not callback
10788  or ((keep = callback(depth++, parse_event_t::array_start, result)) != 0)))
10789  {
10790  // explicitly set result to object to cope with []
10791  result.m_type = value_t::array;
10792  result.m_value = value_t::array;
10793  }
10794 
10795  // read next token
10796  get_token();
10797 
10798  // closing ] -> we are done
10799  if (last_token == lexer::token_type::end_array)
10800  {
10801  get_token();
10802  if (callback and not callback(--depth, parse_event_t::array_end, result))
10803  {
10804  result = basic_json(value_t::discarded);
10805  }
10806  return result;
10807  }
10808 
10809  // no comma is expected here
10810  unexpect(lexer::token_type::value_separator);
10811 
10812  // otherwise: parse values
10813  do
10814  {
10815  // ugly, but could be fixed with loop reorganization
10816  if (last_token == lexer::token_type::value_separator)
10817  {
10818  get_token();
10819  }
10820 
10821  // parse value
10822  auto value = parse_internal(keep);
10823  if (keep and not value.is_discarded())
10824  {
10825  result.push_back(std::move(value));
10826  }
10827  }
10828  while (last_token == lexer::token_type::value_separator);
10829 
10830  // closing ]
10831  expect(lexer::token_type::end_array);
10832  get_token();
10833  if (keep and callback and not callback(--depth, parse_event_t::array_end, result))
10834  {
10835  result = basic_json(value_t::discarded);
10836  }
10837 
10838  return result;
10839  }
10840 
10841  case lexer::token_type::literal_null:
10842  {
10843  get_token();
10844  result.m_type = value_t::null;
10845  break;
10846  }
10847 
10848  case lexer::token_type::value_string:
10849  {
10850  const auto s = m_lexer.get_string();
10851  get_token();
10852  result = basic_json(s);
10853  break;
10854  }
10855 
10856  case lexer::token_type::literal_true:
10857  {
10858  get_token();
10859  result.m_type = value_t::boolean;
10860  result.m_value = true;
10861  break;
10862  }
10863 
10864  case lexer::token_type::literal_false:
10865  {
10866  get_token();
10867  result.m_type = value_t::boolean;
10868  result.m_value = false;
10869  break;
10870  }
10871 
10872  case lexer::token_type::value_number:
10873  {
10874  m_lexer.get_number(result);
10875  get_token();
10876  break;
10877  }
10878 
10879  default:
10880  {
10881  // the last token was unexpected
10882  unexpect(last_token);
10883  }
10884  }
10885 
10886  if (keep and callback and not callback(depth, parse_event_t::value, result))
10887  {
10888  result = basic_json(value_t::discarded);
10889  }
10890  return result;
10891  }
10892 
10893  /// get next token from lexer
10894  typename lexer::token_type get_token()
10895  {
10896  last_token = m_lexer.scan();
10897  return last_token;
10898  }
10899 
10900  void expect(typename lexer::token_type t) const
10901  {
10902  if (t != last_token)
10903  {
10904  std::string error_msg = "parse error - unexpected ";
10905  error_msg += (last_token == lexer::token_type::parse_error ? ("'" + m_lexer.get_token_string() +
10906  "'") :
10907  lexer::token_type_name(last_token));
10908  error_msg += "; expected " + lexer::token_type_name(t);
10909  throw std::invalid_argument(error_msg);
10910  }
10911  }
10912 
10913  void unexpect(typename lexer::token_type t) const
10914  {
10915  if (t == last_token)
10916  {
10917  std::string error_msg = "parse error - unexpected ";
10918  error_msg += (last_token == lexer::token_type::parse_error ? ("'" + m_lexer.get_token_string() +
10919  "'") :
10920  lexer::token_type_name(last_token));
10921  throw std::invalid_argument(error_msg);
10922  }
10923  }
10924 
10925  private:
10926  /// current level of recursion
10927  int depth = 0;
10928  /// callback function
10929  const parser_callback_t callback = nullptr;
10930  /// the type of the last read token
10931  typename lexer::token_type last_token = lexer::token_type::uninitialized;
10932  /// the lexer
10933  lexer m_lexer;
10934  };
10935 
10936  public:
10937  /*!
10938  @brief JSON Pointer
10939 
10940  A JSON pointer defines a string syntax for identifying a specific value
10941  within a JSON document. It can be used with functions `at` and
10942  `operator[]`. Furthermore, JSON pointers are the base for JSON patches.
10943 
10944  @sa [RFC 6901](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6901)
10945 
10946  @since version 2.0.0
10947  */
10948  class json_pointer
10949  {
10950  /// allow basic_json to access private members
10951  friend class basic_json;
10952 
10953  public:
10954  /*!
10955  @brief create JSON pointer
10956 
10957  Create a JSON pointer according to the syntax described in
10958  [Section 3 of RFC6901](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6901#section-3).
10959 
10960  @param[in] s string representing the JSON pointer; if omitted, the
10961  empty string is assumed which references the whole JSON
10962  value
10963 
10964  @throw std::domain_error if reference token is nonempty and does not
10965  begin with a slash (`/`); example: `"JSON pointer must be empty or
10966  begin with /"`
10967  @throw std::domain_error if a tilde (`~`) is not followed by `0`
10968  (representing `~`) or `1` (representing `/`); example: `"escape error:
10969  ~ must be followed with 0 or 1"`
10970 
10971  @liveexample{The example shows the construction several valid JSON
10972  pointers as well as the exceptional behavior.,json_pointer}
10973 
10974  @since version 2.0.0
10975  */
10976  explicit json_pointer(const std::string& s = "")
10977  : reference_tokens(split(s))
10978  {}
10979 
10980  /*!
10981  @brief return a string representation of the JSON pointer
10982 
10983  @invariant For each JSON pointer `ptr`, it holds:
10984  @code {.cpp}
10985  ptr == json_pointer(ptr.to_string());
10986  @endcode
10987 
10988  @return a string representation of the JSON pointer
10989 
10990  @liveexample{The example shows the result of `to_string`.,
10991  json_pointer__to_string}
10992 
10993  @since version 2.0.0
10994  */
10995  std::string to_string() const noexcept
10996  {
10997  return std::accumulate(reference_tokens.begin(),
10998  reference_tokens.end(), std::string{},
10999  [](const std::string & a, const std::string & b)
11000  {
11001  return a + "/" + escape(b);
11002  });
11003  }
11004 
11005  /// @copydoc to_string()
11006  operator std::string() const
11007  {
11008  return to_string();
11009  }
11010 
11011  private:
11012  /// remove and return last reference pointer
11013  std::string pop_back()
11014  {
11015  if (is_root())
11016  {
11017  throw std::domain_error("JSON pointer has no parent");
11018  }
11019 
11020  auto last = reference_tokens.back();
11021  reference_tokens.pop_back();
11022  return last;
11023  }
11024 
11025  /// return whether pointer points to the root document
11026  bool is_root() const
11027  {
11028  return reference_tokens.empty();
11029  }
11030 
11031  json_pointer top() const
11032  {
11033  if (is_root())
11034  {
11035  throw std::domain_error("JSON pointer has no parent");
11036  }
11037 
11038  json_pointer result = *this;
11039  result.reference_tokens = {reference_tokens[0]};
11040  return result;
11041  }
11042 
11043  /*!
11044  @brief create and return a reference to the pointed to value
11045 
11046  @complexity Linear in the number of reference tokens.
11047  */
11048  reference get_and_create(reference j) const
11049  {
11050  pointer result = &j;
11051 
11052  // in case no reference tokens exist, return a reference to the
11053  // JSON value j which will be overwritten by a primitive value
11054  for (const auto& reference_token : reference_tokens)
11055  {
11056  switch (result->m_type)
11057  {
11058  case value_t::null:
11059  {
11060  if (reference_token == "0")
11061  {
11062  // start a new array if reference token is 0
11063  result = &result->operator[](0);
11064  }
11065  else
11066  {
11067  // start a new object otherwise
11068  result = &result->operator[](reference_token);
11069  }
11070  break;
11071  }
11072 
11073  case value_t::object:
11074  {
11075  // create an entry in the object
11076  result = &result->operator[](reference_token);
11077  break;
11078  }
11079 
11080  case value_t::array:
11081  {
11082  // create an entry in the array
11083  result = &result->operator[](static_cast<size_type>(std::stoi(reference_token)));
11084  break;
11085  }
11086 
11087  /*
11088  The following code is only reached if there exists a
11089  reference token _and_ the current value is primitive. In
11090  this case, we have an error situation, because primitive
11091  values may only occur as single value; that is, with an
11092  empty list of reference tokens.
11093  */
11094  default:
11095  {
11096  throw std::domain_error("invalid value to unflatten");
11097  }
11098  }
11099  }
11100 
11101  return *result;
11102  }
11103 
11104  /*!
11105  @brief return a reference to the pointed to value
11106 
11107  @note This version does not throw if a value is not present, but tries
11108  to create nested values instead. For instance, calling this function
11109  with pointer `"/this/that"` on a null value is equivalent to calling
11110  `operator[]("this").operator[]("that")` on that value, effectively
11111  changing the null value to an object.
11112 
11113  @param[in] ptr a JSON value
11114 
11115  @return reference to the JSON value pointed to by the JSON pointer
11116 
11117  @complexity Linear in the length of the JSON pointer.
11118 
11119  @throw std::out_of_range if the JSON pointer can not be resolved
11120  @throw std::domain_error if an array index begins with '0'
11121  @throw std::invalid_argument if an array index was not a number
11122  */
11123  reference get_unchecked(pointer ptr) const
11124  {
11125  for (const auto& reference_token : reference_tokens)
11126  {
11127  // convert null values to arrays or objects before continuing
11128  if (ptr->m_type == value_t::null)
11129  {
11130  // check if reference token is a number
11131  const bool nums = std::all_of(reference_token.begin(),
11132  reference_token.end(),
11133  [](const char x)
11134  {
11135  return std::isdigit(x);
11136  });
11137 
11138  // change value to array for numbers or "-" or to object
11139  // otherwise
11140  if (nums or reference_token == "-")
11141  {
11142  *ptr = value_t::array;
11143  }
11144  else
11145  {
11146  *ptr = value_t::object;
11147  }
11148  }
11149 
11150  switch (ptr->m_type)
11151  {
11152  case value_t::object:
11153  {
11154  // use unchecked object access
11155  ptr = &ptr->operator[](reference_token);
11156  break;
11157  }
11158 
11159  case value_t::array:
11160  {
11161  // error condition (cf. RFC 6901, Sect. 4)
11162  if (reference_token.size() > 1 and reference_token[0] == '0')
11163  {
11164  throw std::domain_error("array index must not begin with '0'");
11165  }
11166 
11167  if (reference_token == "-")
11168  {
11169  // explicityly treat "-" as index beyond the end
11170  ptr = &ptr->operator[](ptr->m_value.array->size());
11171  }
11172  else
11173  {
11174  // convert array index to number; unchecked access
11175  ptr = &ptr->operator[](static_cast<size_type>(std::stoi(reference_token)));
11176  }
11177  break;
11178  }
11179 
11180  default:
11181  {
11182  throw std::out_of_range("unresolved reference token '" + reference_token + "'");
11183  }
11184  }
11185  }
11186 
11187  return *ptr;
11188  }
11189 
11190  reference get_checked(pointer ptr) const
11191  {
11192  for (const auto& reference_token : reference_tokens)
11193  {
11194  switch (ptr->m_type)
11195  {
11196  case value_t::object:
11197  {
11198  // note: at performs range check
11199  ptr = &ptr->at(reference_token);
11200  break;
11201  }
11202 
11203  case value_t::array:
11204  {
11205  if (reference_token == "-")
11206  {
11207  // "-" always fails the range check
11208  throw std::out_of_range("array index '-' (" +
11209  std::to_string(ptr->m_value.array->size()) +
11210  ") is out of range");
11211  }
11212 
11213  // error condition (cf. RFC 6901, Sect. 4)
11214  if (reference_token.size() > 1 and reference_token[0] == '0')
11215  {
11216  throw std::domain_error("array index must not begin with '0'");
11217  }
11218 
11219  // note: at performs range check
11220  ptr = &ptr->at(static_cast<size_type>(std::stoi(reference_token)));
11221  break;
11222  }
11223 
11224  default:
11225  {
11226  throw std::out_of_range("unresolved reference token '" + reference_token + "'");
11227  }
11228  }
11229  }
11230 
11231  return *ptr;
11232  }
11233 
11234  /*!
11235  @brief return a const reference to the pointed to value
11236 
11237  @param[in] ptr a JSON value
11238 
11239  @return const reference to the JSON value pointed to by the JSON
11240  pointer
11241  */
11242  const_reference get_unchecked(const_pointer ptr) const
11243  {
11244  for (const auto& reference_token : reference_tokens)
11245  {
11246  switch (ptr->m_type)
11247  {
11248  case value_t::object:
11249  {
11250  // use unchecked object access
11251  ptr = &ptr->operator[](reference_token);
11252  break;
11253  }
11254 
11255  case value_t::array:
11256  {
11257  if (reference_token == "-")
11258  {
11259  // "-" cannot be used for const access
11260  throw std::out_of_range("array index '-' (" +
11261  std::to_string(ptr->m_value.array->size()) +
11262  ") is out of range");
11263  }
11264 
11265  // error condition (cf. RFC 6901, Sect. 4)
11266  if (reference_token.size() > 1 and reference_token[0] == '0')
11267  {
11268  throw std::domain_error("array index must not begin with '0'");
11269  }
11270 
11271  // use unchecked array access
11272  ptr = &ptr->operator[](static_cast<size_type>(std::stoi(reference_token)));
11273  break;
11274  }
11275 
11276  default:
11277  {
11278  throw std::out_of_range("unresolved reference token '" + reference_token + "'");
11279  }
11280  }
11281  }
11282 
11283  return *ptr;
11284  }
11285 
11286  const_reference get_checked(const_pointer ptr) const
11287  {
11288  for (const auto& reference_token : reference_tokens)
11289  {
11290  switch (ptr->m_type)
11291  {
11292  case value_t::object:
11293  {
11294  // note: at performs range check
11295  ptr = &ptr->at(reference_token);
11296  break;
11297  }
11298 
11299  case value_t::array:
11300  {
11301  if (reference_token == "-")
11302  {
11303  // "-" always fails the range check
11304  throw std::out_of_range("array index '-' (" +
11305  std::to_string(ptr->m_value.array->size()) +
11306  ") is out of range");
11307  }
11308 
11309  // error condition (cf. RFC 6901, Sect. 4)
11310  if (reference_token.size() > 1 and reference_token[0] == '0')
11311  {
11312  throw std::domain_error("array index must not begin with '0'");
11313  }
11314 
11315  // note: at performs range check
11316  ptr = &ptr->at(static_cast<size_type>(std::stoi(reference_token)));
11317  break;
11318  }
11319 
11320  default:
11321  {
11322  throw std::out_of_range("unresolved reference token '" + reference_token + "'");
11323  }
11324  }
11325  }
11326 
11327  return *ptr;
11328  }
11329 
11330  /// split the string input to reference tokens
11331  static std::vector<std::string> split(const std::string& reference_string)
11332  {
11333  std::vector<std::string> result;
11334 
11335  // special case: empty reference string -> no reference tokens
11336  if (reference_string.empty())
11337  {
11338  return result;
11339  }
11340 
11341  // check if nonempty reference string begins with slash
11342  if (reference_string[0] != '/')
11343  {
11344  throw std::domain_error("JSON pointer must be empty or begin with '/'");
11345  }
11346 
11347  // extract the reference tokens:
11348  // - slash: position of the last read slash (or end of string)
11349  // - start: position after the previous slash
11350  for (
11351  // search for the first slash after the first character
11352  size_t slash = reference_string.find_first_of('/', 1),
11353  // set the beginning of the first reference token
11354  start = 1;
11355  // we can stop if start == string::npos+1 = 0
11356  start != 0;
11357  // set the beginning of the next reference token
11358  // (will eventually be 0 if slash == std::string::npos)
11359  start = slash + 1,
11360  // find next slash
11361  slash = reference_string.find_first_of('/', start))
11362  {
11363  // use the text between the beginning of the reference token
11364  // (start) and the last slash (slash).
11365  auto reference_token = reference_string.substr(start, slash - start);
11366 
11367  // check reference tokens are properly escaped
11368  for (size_t pos = reference_token.find_first_of('~');
11369  pos != std::string::npos;
11370  pos = reference_token.find_first_of('~', pos + 1))
11371  {
11372  assert(reference_token[pos] == '~');
11373 
11374  // ~ must be followed by 0 or 1
11375  if (pos == reference_token.size() - 1 or
11376  (reference_token[pos + 1] != '0' and
11377  reference_token[pos + 1] != '1'))
11378  {
11379  throw std::domain_error("escape error: '~' must be followed with '0' or '1'");
11380  }
11381  }
11382 
11383  // finally, store the reference token
11384  unescape(reference_token);
11385  result.push_back(reference_token);
11386  }
11387 
11388  return result;
11389  }
11390 
11391  private:
11392  /*!
11393  @brief replace all occurrences of a substring by another string
11394 
11395  @param[in,out] s the string to manipulate; changed so that all
11396  occurrences of @a f are replaced with @a t
11397  @param[in] f the substring to replace with @a t
11398  @param[in] t the string to replace @a f
11399 
11400  @pre The search string @a f must not be empty.
11401 
11402  @since version 2.0.0
11403  */
11404  static void replace_substring(std::string& s,
11405  const std::string& f,
11406  const std::string& t)
11407  {
11408  assert(not f.empty());
11409 
11410  for (
11411  size_t pos = s.find(f); // find first occurrence of f
11412  pos != std::string::npos; // make sure f was found
11413  s.replace(pos, f.size(), t), // replace with t
11414  pos = s.find(f, pos + t.size()) // find next occurrence of f
11415  );
11416  }
11417 
11418  /// escape tilde and slash
11419  static std::string escape(std::string s)
11420  {
11421  // escape "~"" to "~0" and "/" to "~1"
11422  replace_substring(s, "~", "~0");
11423  replace_substring(s, "/", "~1");
11424  return s;
11425  }
11426 
11427  /// unescape tilde and slash
11428  static void unescape(std::string& s)
11429  {
11430  // first transform any occurrence of the sequence '~1' to '/'
11431  replace_substring(s, "~1", "/");
11432  // then transform any occurrence of the sequence '~0' to '~'
11433  replace_substring(s, "~0", "~");
11434  }
11435 
11436  /*!
11437  @param[in] reference_string the reference string to the current value
11438  @param[in] value the value to consider
11439  @param[in,out] result the result object to insert values to
11440 
11441  @note Empty objects or arrays are flattened to `null`.
11442  */
11443  static void flatten(const std::string& reference_string,
11444  const basic_json& value,
11445  basic_json& result)
11446  {
11447  switch (value.m_type)
11448  {
11449  case value_t::array:
11450  {
11451  if (value.m_value.array->empty())
11452  {
11453  // flatten empty array as null
11454  result[reference_string] = nullptr;
11455  }
11456  else
11457  {
11458  // iterate array and use index as reference string
11459  for (size_t i = 0; i < value.m_value.array->size(); ++i)
11460  {
11461  flatten(reference_string + "/" + std::to_string(i),
11462  value.m_value.array->operator[](i), result);
11463  }
11464  }
11465  break;
11466  }
11467 
11468  case value_t::object:
11469  {
11470  if (value.m_value.object->empty())
11471  {
11472  // flatten empty object as null
11473  result[reference_string] = nullptr;
11474  }
11475  else
11476  {
11477  // iterate object and use keys as reference string
11478  for (const auto& element : *value.m_value.object)
11479  {
11480  flatten(reference_string + "/" + escape(element.first),
11481  element.second, result);
11482  }
11483  }
11484  break;
11485  }
11486 
11487  default:
11488  {
11489  // add primitive value with its reference string
11490  result[reference_string] = value;
11491  break;
11492  }
11493  }
11494  }
11495 
11496  /*!
11497  @param[in] value flattened JSON
11498 
11499  @return unflattened JSON
11500  */
11501  static basic_json unflatten(const basic_json& value)
11502  {
11503  if (not value.is_object())
11504  {
11505  throw std::domain_error("only objects can be unflattened");
11506  }
11507 
11508  basic_json result;
11509 
11510  // iterate the JSON object values
11511  for (const auto& element : *value.m_value.object)
11512  {
11513  if (not element.second.is_primitive())
11514  {
11515  throw std::domain_error("values in object must be primitive");
11516  }
11517 
11518  // assign value to reference pointed to by JSON pointer; Note
11519  // that if the JSON pointer is "" (i.e., points to the whole
11520  // value), function get_and_create returns a reference to
11521  // result itself. An assignment will then create a primitive
11522  // value.
11523  json_pointer(element.first).get_and_create(result) = element.second;
11524  }
11525 
11526  return result;
11527  }
11528 
11529  private:
11530  /// the reference tokens
11531  std::vector<std::string> reference_tokens {};
11532  };
11533 
11534  //////////////////////////
11535  // JSON Pointer support //
11536  //////////////////////////
11537 
11538  /// @name JSON Pointer functions
11539  /// @{
11540 
11541  /*!
11542  @brief access specified element via JSON Pointer
11543 
11544  Uses a JSON pointer to retrieve a reference to the respective JSON value.
11545  No bound checking is performed. Similar to @ref operator[](const typename
11546  object_t::key_type&), `null` values are created in arrays and objects if
11547  necessary.
11548 
11549  In particular:
11550  - If the JSON pointer points to an object key that does not exist, it
11551  is created an filled with a `null` value before a reference to it
11552  is returned.
11553  - If the JSON pointer points to an array index that does not exist, it
11554  is created an filled with a `null` value before a reference to it
11555  is returned. All indices between the current maximum and the given
11556  index are also filled with `null`.
11557  - The special value `-` is treated as a synonym for the index past the
11558  end.
11559 
11560  @param[in] ptr a JSON pointer
11561 
11562  @return reference to the element pointed to by @a ptr
11563 
11564  @complexity Constant.
11565 
11566  @throw std::out_of_range if the JSON pointer can not be resolved
11567  @throw std::domain_error if an array index begins with '0'
11568  @throw std::invalid_argument if an array index was not a number
11569 
11570  @liveexample{The behavior is shown in the example.,operatorjson_pointer}
11571 
11572  @since version 2.0.0
11573  */
11574  reference operator[](const json_pointer& ptr)
11575  {
11576  return ptr.get_unchecked(this);
11577  }
11578 
11579  /*!
11580  @brief access specified element via JSON Pointer
11581 
11582  Uses a JSON pointer to retrieve a reference to the respective JSON value.
11583  No bound checking is performed. The function does not change the JSON
11584  value; no `null` values are created. In particular, the the special value
11585  `-` yields an exception.
11586 
11587  @param[in] ptr JSON pointer to the desired element
11588 
11589  @return const reference to the element pointed to by @a ptr
11590 
11591  @complexity Constant.
11592 
11593  @throw std::out_of_range if the JSON pointer can not be resolved
11594  @throw std::domain_error if an array index begins with '0'
11595  @throw std::invalid_argument if an array index was not a number
11596 
11597  @liveexample{The behavior is shown in the example.,operatorjson_pointer_const}
11598 
11599  @since version 2.0.0
11600  */
11601  const_reference operator[](const json_pointer& ptr) const
11602  {
11603  return ptr.get_unchecked(this);
11604  }
11605 
11606  /*!
11607  @brief access specified element via JSON Pointer
11608 
11609  Returns a reference to the element at with specified JSON pointer @a ptr,
11610  with bounds checking.
11611 
11612  @param[in] ptr JSON pointer to the desired element
11613 
11614  @return reference to the element pointed to by @a ptr
11615 
11616  @complexity Constant.
11617 
11618  @throw std::out_of_range if the JSON pointer can not be resolved
11619  @throw std::domain_error if an array index begins with '0'
11620  @throw std::invalid_argument if an array index was not a number
11621 
11622  @liveexample{The behavior is shown in the example.,at_json_pointer}
11623 
11624  @since version 2.0.0
11625  */
11626  reference at(const json_pointer& ptr)
11627  {
11628  return ptr.get_checked(this);
11629  }
11630 
11631  /*!
11632  @brief access specified element via JSON Pointer
11633 
11634  Returns a const reference to the element at with specified JSON pointer @a
11635  ptr, with bounds checking.
11636 
11637  @param[in] ptr JSON pointer to the desired element
11638 
11639  @return reference to the element pointed to by @a ptr
11640 
11641  @complexity Constant.
11642 
11643  @throw std::out_of_range if the JSON pointer can not be resolved
11644  @throw std::domain_error if an array index begins with '0'
11645  @throw std::invalid_argument if an array index was not a number
11646 
11647  @liveexample{The behavior is shown in the example.,at_json_pointer_const}
11648 
11649  @since version 2.0.0
11650  */
11651  const_reference at(const json_pointer& ptr) const
11652  {
11653  return ptr.get_checked(this);
11654  }
11655 
11656  /*!
11657  @brief return flattened JSON value
11658 
11659  The function creates a JSON object whose keys are JSON pointers (see [RFC
11660  6901](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6901)) and whose values are all
11661  primitive. The original JSON value can be restored using the @ref
11662  unflatten() function.
11663 
11664  @return an object that maps JSON pointers to primitve values
11665 
11666  @note Empty objects and arrays are flattened to `null` and will not be
11667  reconstructed correctly by the @ref unflatten() function.
11668 
11669  @complexity Linear in the size the JSON value.
11670 
11671  @liveexample{The following code shows how a JSON object is flattened to an
11672  object whose keys consist of JSON pointers.,flatten}
11673 
11674  @sa @ref unflatten() for the reverse function
11675 
11676  @since version 2.0.0
11677  */
11678  basic_json flatten() const
11679  {
11680  basic_json result(value_t::object);
11681  json_pointer::flatten("", *this, result);
11682  return result;
11683  }
11684 
11685  /*!
11686  @brief unflatten a previously flattened JSON value
11687 
11688  The function restores the arbitrary nesting of a JSON value that has been
11689  flattened before using the @ref flatten() function. The JSON value must
11690  meet certain constraints:
11691  1. The value must be an object.
11692  2. The keys must be JSON pointers (see
11693  [RFC 6901](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6901))
11694  3. The mapped values must be primitive JSON types.
11695 
11696  @return the original JSON from a flattened version
11697 
11698  @note Empty objects and arrays are flattened by @ref flatten() to `null`
11699  values and can not unflattened to their original type. Apart from
11700  this example, for a JSON value `j`, the following is always true:
11701  `j == j.flatten().unflatten()`.
11702 
11703  @complexity Linear in the size the JSON value.
11704 
11705  @liveexample{The following code shows how a flattened JSON object is
11706  unflattened into the original nested JSON object.,unflatten}
11707 
11708  @sa @ref flatten() for the reverse function
11709 
11710  @since version 2.0.0
11711  */
11712  basic_json unflatten() const
11713  {
11714  return json_pointer::unflatten(*this);
11715  }
11716 
11717  /// @}
11718 
11719  //////////////////////////
11720  // JSON Patch functions //
11721  //////////////////////////
11722 
11723  /// @name JSON Patch functions
11724  /// @{
11725 
11726  /*!
11727  @brief applies a JSON patch
11728 
11729  [JSON Patch](http://jsonpatch.com) defines a JSON document structure for
11730  expressing a sequence of operations to apply to a JSON) document. With
11731  this funcion, a JSON Patch is applied to the current JSON value by
11732  executing all operations from the patch.
11733 
11734  @param[in] json_patch JSON patch document
11735  @return patched document
11736 
11737  @note The application of a patch is atomic: Either all operations succeed
11738  and the patched document is returned or an exception is thrown. In
11739  any case, the original value is not changed: the patch is applied
11740  to a copy of the value.
11741 
11742  @throw std::out_of_range if a JSON pointer inside the patch could not
11743  be resolved successfully in the current JSON value; example: `"key baz
11744  not found"`
11745  @throw invalid_argument if the JSON patch is malformed (e.g., mandatory
11746  attributes are missing); example: `"operation add must have member path"`
11747 
11748  @complexity Linear in the size of the JSON value and the length of the
11749  JSON patch. As usually only a fraction of the JSON value is affected by
11750  the patch, the complexity can usually be neglected.
11751 
11752  @liveexample{The following code shows how a JSON patch is applied to a
11753  value.,patch}
11754 
11755  @sa @ref diff -- create a JSON patch by comparing two JSON values
11756 
11757  @sa [RFC 6902 (JSON Patch)](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6902)
11758  @sa [RFC 6901 (JSON Pointer)](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6901)
11759 
11760  @since version 2.0.0
11761  */
11762  basic_json patch(const basic_json& json_patch) const
11763  {
11764  // make a working copy to apply the patch to
11765  basic_json result = *this;
11766 
11767  // the valid JSON Patch operations
11768  enum class patch_operations {add, remove, replace, move, copy, test, invalid};
11769 
11770  const auto get_op = [](const std::string op)
11771  {
11772  if (op == "add")
11773  {
11774  return patch_operations::add;
11775  }
11776  if (op == "remove")
11777  {
11778  return patch_operations::remove;
11779  }
11780  if (op == "replace")
11781  {
11782  return patch_operations::replace;
11783  }
11784  if (op == "move")
11785  {
11786  return patch_operations::move;
11787  }
11788  if (op == "copy")
11789  {
11790  return patch_operations::copy;
11791  }
11792  if (op == "test")
11793  {
11794  return patch_operations::test;
11795  }
11796 
11797  return patch_operations::invalid;
11798  };
11799 
11800  // wrapper for "add" operation; add value at ptr
11801  const auto operation_add = [&result](json_pointer & ptr, basic_json val)
11802  {
11803  // adding to the root of the target document means replacing it
11804  if (ptr.is_root())
11805  {
11806  result = val;
11807  }
11808  else
11809  {
11810  // make sure the top element of the pointer exists
11811  json_pointer top_pointer = ptr.top();
11812  if (top_pointer != ptr)
11813  {
11814  result.at(top_pointer);
11815  }
11816 
11817  // get reference to parent of JSON pointer ptr
11818  const auto last_path = ptr.pop_back();
11819  basic_json& parent = result[ptr];
11820 
11821  switch (parent.m_type)
11822  {
11823  case value_t::null:
11824  case value_t::object:
11825  {
11826  // use operator[] to add value
11827  parent[last_path] = val;
11828  break;
11829  }
11830 
11831  case value_t::array:
11832  {
11833  if (last_path == "-")
11834  {
11835  // special case: append to back
11836  parent.push_back(val);
11837  }
11838  else
11839  {
11840  const auto idx = std::stoi(last_path);
11841  if (static_cast<size_type>(idx) > parent.size())
11842  {
11843  // avoid undefined behavior
11844  throw std::out_of_range("array index " + std::to_string(idx) + " is out of range");
11845  }
11846  else
11847  {
11848  // default case: insert add offset
11849  parent.insert(parent.begin() + static_cast<difference_type>(idx), val);
11850  }
11851  }
11852  break;
11853  }
11854 
11855  default:
11856  {
11857  // if there exists a parent it cannot be primitive
11858  assert(false); // LCOV_EXCL_LINE
11859  }
11860  }
11861  }
11862  };
11863 
11864  // wrapper for "remove" operation; remove value at ptr
11865  const auto operation_remove = [&result](json_pointer & ptr)
11866  {
11867  // get reference to parent of JSON pointer ptr
11868  const auto last_path = ptr.pop_back();
11869  basic_json& parent = result.at(ptr);
11870 
11871  // remove child
11872  if (parent.is_object())
11873  {
11874  // perform range check
11875  auto it = parent.find(last_path);
11876  if (it != parent.end())
11877  {
11878  parent.erase(it);
11879  }
11880  else
11881  {
11882  throw std::out_of_range("key '" + last_path + "' not found");
11883  }
11884  }
11885  else if (parent.is_array())
11886  {
11887  // note erase performs range check
11888  parent.erase(static_cast<size_type>(std::stoi(last_path)));
11889  }
11890  };
11891 
11892  // type check
11893  if (not json_patch.is_array())
11894  {
11895  // a JSON patch must be an array of objects
11896  throw std::invalid_argument("JSON patch must be an array of objects");
11897  }
11898 
11899  // iterate and apply th eoperations
11900  for (const auto& val : json_patch)
11901  {
11902  // wrapper to get a value for an operation
11903  const auto get_value = [&val](const std::string & op,
11904  const std::string & member,
11905  bool string_type) -> basic_json&
11906  {
11907  // find value
11908  auto it = val.m_value.object->find(member);
11909 
11910  // context-sensitive error message
11911  const auto error_msg = (op == "op") ? "operation" : "operation '" + op + "'";
11912 
11913  // check if desired value is present
11914  if (it == val.m_value.object->end())
11915  {
11916  throw std::invalid_argument(error_msg + " must have member '" + member + "'");
11917  }
11918 
11919  // check if result is of type string
11920  if (string_type and not it->second.is_string())
11921  {
11922  throw std::invalid_argument(error_msg + " must have string member '" + member + "'");
11923  }
11924 
11925  // no error: return value
11926  return it->second;
11927  };
11928 
11929  // type check
11930  if (not val.is_object())
11931  {
11932  throw std::invalid_argument("JSON patch must be an array of objects");
11933  }
11934 
11935  // collect mandatory members
11936  const std::string op = get_value("op", "op", true);
11937  const std::string path = get_value(op, "path", true);
11938  json_pointer ptr(path);
11939 
11940  switch (get_op(op))
11941  {
11942  case patch_operations::add:
11943  {
11944  operation_add(ptr, get_value("add", "value", false));
11945  break;
11946  }
11947 
11948  case patch_operations::remove:
11949  {
11950  operation_remove(ptr);
11951  break;
11952  }
11953 
11954  case patch_operations::replace:
11955  {
11956  // the "path" location must exist - use at()
11957  result.at(ptr) = get_value("replace", "value", false);
11958  break;
11959  }
11960 
11961  case patch_operations::move:
11962  {
11963  const std::string from_path = get_value("move", "from", true);
11964  json_pointer from_ptr(from_path);
11965 
11966  // the "from" location must exist - use at()
11967  basic_json v = result.at(from_ptr);
11968 
11969  // The move operation is functionally identical to a
11970  // "remove" operation on the "from" location, followed
11971  // immediately by an "add" operation at the target
11972  // location with the value that was just removed.
11973  operation_remove(from_ptr);
11974  operation_add(ptr, v);
11975  break;
11976  }
11977 
11978  case patch_operations::copy:
11979  {
11980  const std::string from_path = get_value("copy", "from", true);;
11981  const json_pointer from_ptr(from_path);
11982 
11983  // the "from" location must exist - use at()
11984  result[ptr] = result.at(from_ptr);
11985  break;
11986  }
11987 
11988  case patch_operations::test:
11989  {
11990  bool success = false;
11991  try
11992  {
11993  // check if "value" matches the one at "path"
11994  // the "path" location must exist - use at()
11995  success = (result.at(ptr) == get_value("test", "value", false));
11996  }
11997  catch (std::out_of_range&)
11998  {
11999  // ignore out of range errors: success remains false
12000  }
12001 
12002  // throw an exception if test fails
12003  if (not success)
12004  {
12005  throw std::domain_error("unsuccessful: " + val.dump());
12006  }
12007 
12008  break;
12009  }
12010 
12011  case patch_operations::invalid:
12012  {
12013  // op must be "add", "remove", "replace", "move", "copy", or
12014  // "test"
12015  throw std::invalid_argument("operation value '" + op + "' is invalid");
12016  }
12017  }
12018  }
12019 
12020  return result;
12021  }
12022 
12023  /*!
12024  @brief creates a diff as a JSON patch
12025 
12026  Creates a [JSON Patch](http://jsonpatch.com) so that value @a source can
12027  be changed into the value @a target by calling @ref patch function.
12028 
12029  @invariant For two JSON values @a source and @a target, the following code
12030  yields always `true`:
12031  @code {.cpp}
12032  source.patch(diff(source, target)) == target;
12033  @endcode
12034 
12035  @note Currently, only `remove`, `add`, and `replace` operations are
12036  generated.
12037 
12038  @param[in] source JSON value to copare from
12039  @param[in] target JSON value to copare against
12040  @param[in] path helper value to create JSON pointers
12041 
12042  @return a JSON patch to convert the @a source to @a target
12043 
12044  @complexity Linear in the lengths of @a source and @a target.
12045 
12046  @liveexample{The following code shows how a JSON patch is created as a
12047  diff for two JSON values.,diff}
12048 
12049  @sa @ref patch -- apply a JSON patch
12050 
12051  @sa [RFC 6902 (JSON Patch)](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6902)
12052 
12053  @since version 2.0.0
12054  */
12055  static basic_json diff(const basic_json& source,
12056  const basic_json& target,
12057  const std::string& path = "")
12058  {
12059  // the patch
12060  basic_json result(value_t::array);
12061 
12062  // if the values are the same, return empty patch
12063  if (source == target)
12064  {
12065  return result;
12066  }
12067 
12068  if (source.type() != target.type())
12069  {
12070  // different types: replace value
12071  result.push_back(
12072  {
12073  {"op", "replace"},
12074  {"path", path},
12075  {"value", target}
12076  });
12077  }
12078  else
12079  {
12080  switch (source.type())
12081  {
12082  case value_t::array:
12083  {
12084  // first pass: traverse common elements
12085  size_t i = 0;
12086  while (i < source.size() and i < target.size())
12087  {
12088  // recursive call to compare array values at index i
12089  auto temp_diff = diff(source[i], target[i], path + "/" + std::to_string(i));
12090  result.insert(result.end(), temp_diff.begin(), temp_diff.end());
12091  ++i;
12092  }
12093 
12094  // i now reached the end of at least one array
12095  // in a second pass, traverse the remaining elements
12096 
12097  // remove my remaining elements
12098  const auto end_index = static_cast<difference_type>(result.size());
12099  while (i < source.size())
12100  {
12101  // add operations in reverse order to avoid invalid
12102  // indices
12103  result.insert(result.begin() + end_index, object(
12104  {
12105  {"op", "remove"},
12106  {"path", path + "/" + std::to_string(i)}
12107  }));
12108  ++i;
12109  }
12110 
12111  // add other remaining elements
12112  while (i < target.size())
12113  {
12114  result.push_back(
12115  {
12116  {"op", "add"},
12117  {"path", path + "/" + std::to_string(i)},
12118  {"value", target[i]}
12119  });
12120  ++i;
12121  }
12122 
12123  break;
12124  }
12125 
12126  case value_t::object:
12127  {
12128  // first pass: traverse this object's elements
12129  for (auto it = source.begin(); it != source.end(); ++it)
12130  {
12131  // escape the key name to be used in a JSON patch
12132  const auto key = json_pointer::escape(it.key());
12133 
12134  if (target.find(it.key()) != target.end())
12135  {
12136  // recursive call to compare object values at key it
12137  auto temp_diff = diff(it.value(), target[it.key()], path + "/" + key);
12138  result.insert(result.end(), temp_diff.begin(), temp_diff.end());
12139  }
12140  else
12141  {
12142  // found a key that is not in o -> remove it
12143  result.push_back(object(
12144  {
12145  {"op", "remove"},
12146  {"path", path + "/" + key}
12147  }));
12148  }
12149  }
12150 
12151  // second pass: traverse other object's elements
12152  for (auto it = target.begin(); it != target.end(); ++it)
12153  {
12154  if (source.find(it.key()) == source.end())
12155  {
12156  // found a key that is not in this -> add it
12157  const auto key = json_pointer::escape(it.key());
12158  result.push_back(
12159  {
12160  {"op", "add"},
12161  {"path", path + "/" + key},
12162  {"value", it.value()}
12163  });
12164  }
12165  }
12166 
12167  break;
12168  }
12169 
12170  default:
12171  {
12172  // both primitive type: replace value
12173  result.push_back(
12174  {
12175  {"op", "replace"},
12176  {"path", path},
12177  {"value", target}
12178  });
12179  break;
12180  }
12181  }
12182  }
12183 
12184  return result;
12185  }
12186 
12187  /// @}
12188 };
12189
